<HEADLINE>GHK consign sad Selkirk to the drop</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GHK director of rugby Andy Little was amazed and surprised at his side's fast
reversal of fortunes at Philiphaugh. Down 14-0 at half-time, GHK stepped up a
gear in the second half to consign Selkirk to Division Three next season.
Both clubs still have cup glory to seek, but it is doubtful if any game will
match the complete transformation on Saturday when GHK rattled up 40 points in
a breathtaking second half, for which the final whistle was welcome relief for
the home side.
There was no indication of such a turnaround at half-time, when Selkirk led
with a try by Darren Hulme and three Rodney Pow penalty goals. But, according
to Little, the turning point was Graham Agnew's opening try in 47 minutes, when
he took full back Gerry Hawkes' pass to go over in the right corner.
GHK went on to add a further five tries as Selkirk ran out of steam, and the
home side was left to regret not having built on their first-half dominance.
Tries by Cammy Litttle, Murray Wallace, Harry Bassi, then Agnew and Wallace
again added to the Selkirk misery, with John McLeod slotting five conversions.
Selkirk's consolation was two further Pow penalties.
For Selkirk coach John Rutherford it was almost unbearable. ``I am gutted,'' he
said. However, selector Nick Bihel said they had to look to the future: ``We
are down, but we are by no means out. We will be back.'' He added that Selkirk
would have to bring in younger players for the regional league matches.
Rutherford is to continue as coach, but a question mark must hang over the
future of international centre Scott Nichol. He confirmed that he would be
staying until the end of the season, but beyond that he could say no more.
Selkirk - R Pow; D Hunter, K Johnston, D Gage, D Hulme; S Nichol, A Lindores; B
Johnson, D Graham, I Purves, D Cameron, K Sinclair, K McConnell, R Evans, D
Nichol. Replacement - M Jaffray for Hunter (71min.).
GHK - G Hawkes; G Agnew, H Bassi, T Sanderson, G Caldwell; J McLeod, C Little;
S Gray, C Docherty, G McIlwham, K Wilson, C Du Plessis, S Unkles, M Wallace, R
Sweeney.
Referee - D Girdwood (Stewart's Melville).
SCORERS: Selkirk - Hulme, 1t; Pow, 5p. GHK - Agnew, 2t; Wallace, 2t; Little,
1t; Bassi, 1t; McLeod, 5c.
Selkirk 20, GHK 40
</TEXT>
