<HEADLINE>Gipsies and the gospel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AILEEN LITTLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TILLY WILSON has until April to complete post-graduate research on the
relationship between the church and the gospel and how the two interact with
the travelling community, its culture, and traditions. Heady stuff. But then
Wilson is uniquely qualified to tackle it. For a start, she was born into the
gipsy community herself; and second, overcoming a lack of formal education and
with not a single school exam pass to her name, she succeeded in becoming a
Church of Scotland minister. This month marks the fifth anniversary of her
ordination.
During that period the Reverend Matilda Wilson has fulfilled a unique role. She
is sole non-Catholic cleric responsible for the spiritual welfare of travellers
in the UK. ``It was an area the national church hadn't covered. I didn't have
to build up a relationship first; I knew how we travellers think,'' she says.
Eight months of the year Wilson works as associate minister of Greenhills
Church, East Kilbride; for the rest, operating under the auspices of the Church
of Scotland's national mission department, she takes off on the caravan trail
with a Yorkshire terrier to a world where she claims pastoral care is part of
everyday life.
Innate in travellers, she says, is an absence of class distinction based on
material possessions - a bond of equality enables gipsies worldwide to
recognise each other. Open with her own kind, restless and often defensive in
the settled community, she has spent the past decade (she trained first as a
Church of Scotland deaconess) with a foot uneasily in both camps.
It has been far from straightforward. When her own aspirations were nearing
fulfilment, relationships with kinsfolk were often strained. Wilson has since
led four members of her extended family to become professed Christians. Her
freewheeling gipsy temperament made formal study and routine difficult. Hardest
of all, Wilson frequently comes up against discrimination on both sides of the
divide. Sympathetically she cites the example of a Christian primary school
head forced to choose between welcoming children from a nearby site, and losing
established pupils when prejudiced parents threatened to withdraw them.
The Edinburgh-based Scottish Gipsy/Travellers Association tells a similar
story. ``We're having to deny our heritage. Even housed-up travellers are
discriminated against,'' says the association spokesman who, as a traveller
himself, believes he would cease to find work in the building trade if he were
named.
While Tilly Wilson's professional responsibilities lie first and foremost with
the spiritual welfare of her flock in East Kilbride and her people on the road,
she acts as SGTA resource person, helping to raise awareness of the travellers'
lifestyle. It is an education process she continues through her ministerial
role by accepting invitations to address rotaries and guilds several times a
month. The word gipsy, she tells her audience, is regarded as pejorative. But
in recent years it has regained some favour to distinguish between New Agers
who travel through choice, and gipsies who travel through instinct. All,
however, are subject to the same restrictions and thereby hang some sorry tales.
``I can no longer always visit my relatives and family in Scotland's 33
designated sites. Regulations curtail our freedom,'' explains Wilson. The
year-old Criminal Justice Bill means travellers have to book sites ahead.
Permission to move on depends on the outcome of local council vetting as to
conduct at the last site visited. Equally inhibiting is a stipulation that most
pitches must house only one caravan - while most travelling families possess
two. The SGTA is unhappy about high rents at campsites too. ``They run from #36
to #65 a week, while council house rents are #30 a week in some towns,'' says
the SGTA spokesman.
Scotland's gipsy community (anything between 23,000 and 40,000 - it's difficult
to keep track of housed travellers) is part of Europe's biggest minority group.
According to Isabel Fonseca's book on the history of the Roma people, out this
month*, gipsy activists are edging into the world of international diplomacy
and the gipsy identity is officially recognised by agencies of the UN.
But the author's findings on travellers' predilection for religion - she
records that they have no God and live entirely for the present - strikes Tilly
Wilson as stunningly off course. Certainly it doesn't square with the thousands
of Catholic travellers who descend on Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer every year to
honour St Sarah, patron saint of travellers. ``Even folk who profess not to be
Christian have a real sense of a power ordering the universe,'' says Wilson.
``But the majority do claim to be Christian. There's an evangelical movement, a
Protestant revival across Europe. There is spirituality and the Church of
Scotland has recognised that a more flexible approach is needed to draw it
out.''
n Bury Me Standing - The Gypsies and their Journey, by Isabel Fonseca, Chatto,
#18.99.
Traveller Tilly Wilson became a minister, and now helps others down the road to
conversion. AILEEN LITTLE explains
</TEXT>
