<HEADLINE>Hugh too</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DOUGHERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175684</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Naming your son after you is the most stupid thing a father can do, HUGH
DOUGHERTY
has discovered
THERE are lots of dads who make the same basic mistake as me. For reference to
the births column of The Herald reveals a distressing number of proud fathers
who fall into the trap of naming a son after themselves.
Nineteen years ago, just like them, we named our first son Hugh. And it seemed
quite logical, with the name stretching back over the generations to the
Donegal roots of the clan Dochartaigh, to give it its proper title.
The problem is that Young Shug, now a second-year university student, with a
regular Saturday job, receives nearly as much mail as I do.
Regularly, I open his mail by mistake, while he returns the insult,
intentionally or otherwise, usually working on the assumption that if it looks
like a bill, it's mine, with the more interesting or hopeful going to him.
X-ray vision, holding letters up against a bright light, and speculation about
the postmark are all the tricks of the trade used to try to ensure that you
don't open Hugh Dougherty's mail, if, that is, it's the wrong Hugh Dougherty.
Who, all those years ago, as the new baby looked up at you with a milky smile,
could have imagined that such problems were on the horizon? Naming him Hugh
seemed like a good idea at the time.
But it's the events of recent weeks that have convinced me, for all time, that
naming your son after you is the most dangerous and stupid action you can take
as a father.
Basically, Young Shug has a current account with a leading building society.
And I also have an account with the same society.
A new cheque book arrives, addressed to Hugh Dougherty, my old one has expired,
and we're going off for a week in Yorkshire.
So, in all innocence, I pocket the cheque book and spend a happy week writing
cheques for the rent of a cottage, film, and sundry other holiday pursuits.
It was only when the real Hugh Dougherty went to withdraw funds from his
account with a cash card that the problem came to light. The machine referred
him to his branch where a bemused cashier spelled out the tale of woe to him.
He had been writing cheques: funds were almost at zero.
And then the penny dropped. Young Shug chequed it all out, and it transpired
that he had not been subject to a phantom withdrawal but that his father had
been writing the cheques using HIS book.
Incredibly, even though the signature was wrong, the cheque card didn't match
the account, and the account number was wrong in any case, the building society
paid out every time to the payees, to the tune of #237.
``Technically,'' a now amused cashier told her customer, ``your dad has
committed an offence.''
So it was that the reckoning came that night at home. And how he lorded it over
me.
All those lectures about managing your money were thrown back with interest.
And there was the most biting comment of all: ``Most students have to take
loans to finish their courses. But here's a case of a student giving a loan to
his father. I must be the only one in the country.''
He's never actually revealed to me what the cashier said when he arrived at the
counter with a cheque reading ``Pay Hugh Dougherty Two Hundred and Thirty Seven
Pounds, signed Hugh Dougherty,'' but I did make sure that it was the right
cheque book this time.
Take note: baby sons grow up. They get mail. They even have cheque books, and,
if they have the same name as their father, disaster is the only outcome.
Being swayed by paternal pride and naming that new son after you, can be a
costly mistake you can't afford to bank on. The best thing you can do with a
name is cheque it out for the future.
</TEXT>
