<HEADLINE>Living up to their roots Generations of women share both joy and heartache but their world has grown to become a place of greater freedom, writes Joan McFadden</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOAN McFADDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175685</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE novelist A S Byatt said recently that what she likes most about being a
woman in the 1990s is a kind of freedom that is the opposite of waiting to be
asked to dance. But have women truly never had it so good? Are greater freedoms
and expectations not a mixed blessing? Has a woman's lot really improved? Has
feminism led us on a merry dance, albeit to our own tunes?
In her latest book, Hidden Lives, the writer Margaret Forster has produced what
appears to be an autobiographical account of her family's hardships and the
sacrifices they made, beginning with the birth of her grandmother in 1869.
Although secrets surrounding her grandmother's early life first inspired her to
delve into family history, the end result encompasses a great deal more than a
simple personal chronology.
This is a commentary on women, how their lives and aspirations have changed
over three generations. Forster provides a documentary full of relevant
details, which results in a vivid portrait of three generations of ``ordinary''
women.
She asks us to recall how bad things once were, to look at the punishing life
of a woman such as her grandmother, Margaret Ann. A working-class girl born in
1869, she accepted her lot and, despite the hardships endured, Margaret Ann
felt she had succeeded, especially in material matters such as actually being a
house owner.
Her worry for her daughters took over a great deal of her life, to the extent
she wanted to make their decisions for them, and ultimately had to accept
rather than welcome the lives they led. The last few months of her life were
overshadowed by unhappiness and this pattern repeated itself in her daughter,
Forster's mother, Lily, who ended her days consumed with envy at how her
daughter lived and the choices she had before her.
She could see how life had changed and was continuing to change, but was bitter
there appeared to be nothing for her in this improvement in the lot of women.
There is such sadness in this summing-up of a life, which in many ways
illustrated the transition between life in the forties and fifities and now.
Margaret Ann accepted her life, Forster's mother resented hers, and now the
daughter is happily doing exactly what she wants with hers.
Life is undoubtedly better for women when compared to a century ago and this
welcome change is duplicated throughout generations of women in this country,
as I found when I talked to one woman about her family's story.
Johanna MacLean was born in 1883. In 1974, her great-grand-daughter was named
Joanna in her memory. The decades separating their births have seen many
changes for women, and yet throughout the years there are also constant
parallels.
Johanna was the youngest of six girls whose father was a farm manager on the
Balranald Estate on North Uist. She had a good education and yet left school at
15, as any further education was rare for women at that time, especially in the
Highlands and islands. The most obvious job available was in domestic service,
despite both her educated status and family background, and she duly took up a
post at the Church of Scotland manse in Castlebay on Barra.
It was extremely hard work, with long hours and very little time off, but
Johanna had no real options. When she decided to move to Glasgow a couple of
years later she did so in the same line of work and was employed by the
Marshall family, the well-known food manufacturers.
PURELY by chance they discovered she was an excellent cook, and sent her to
``dough school''. When she completed her course they continued to employ her,
but as a cook, which was a much higher status than her previous post. The job
still involved long hours and hard physical work, but was better paid, offered
an outlet for her obvious talents and avoided the sheer drudgery of life as a
domestic servant.
She got married at 30 - on the 12th of the 12th, 1912 - to Angus Maclean, and
returned to North Uist. Angus had the reputation of being a ``successful
crofter'', a rare accolade and one which was achieved only through sheer hard
work. Johanna's life also became much harder as they lived in a croft without
running water, with all clothes washed by hand in water heated on a big stove,
and lighting provided by paraffin lamps.
Their first son, Archie, only lived for six months, during which time he
apparently cried constantly in pain. The healthcare available was inadequate
both in diagnosis and cure, although it is almost certain that he suffered from
pyloric stenosis, which is now easily treated.
Angus and Johanna went on to have five more children, and she died of a stroke
at 50, having suffered ill health for some time before her death. Angus died
eight years later at the age of 63, almost literally working himself to death.
Their elder daughter, Mary-Flora, was born in 1915, and considers her life easy
in comparison to her mother's, although she does remember her mother as a very
happy person. She left school initially at 14 to help at home, but returned a
year later and finally gained her Leaving Certificate at 16.
The following two years were spent looking after her ailing mother, and
continuing to run the home and care for the rest of her family after Johanna
died. By the time she was 21 her younger sister, Mary, was old enough to take
over, and Mary-Flora moved to Glasgow to train as a nurse.
She was quickly disillusioned by poor pay and dreadful working conditions, and
within a matter of weeks sat the Civil Service exam instead hoping to get a job
in the ``social'' in Greenock, looking after orphaned babies. However, the
place offered to her was in the prison service based in the Women's Prison in
Duke Street.
Her probationary year was divided into four training periods, spent in turn in
the laundry, cookhouse, cutting-room, and reception. There was a short exam at
the end of each training session and a longer exam at the end of the year, all
of which Mary-Flora passed. Now qualified, she continued to work in the
different departments as a supervisor.
She thoroughly enjoyed her time in Glasgow, finding the work ``easy'' and her
living quarters comfortable. Food and laundry were provided and there was a
great social life, although theceilidhs and dances were rather curtailed by
having to be back sharp at 11 in the Officers' Quarters. Then she met Johnnie
Macleod, and started courting. Everything was going well, until she decided to
go home on leave. Johnnie was very keen and wanted to buy her an engagement
ring before she left, but Mary-Flora persuaded him to wait until she returned.
That decision changed her life. The ferry-crossing to Uist was stormy and she
clearly remembers the discomfort she felt. She also remembers that she was
wearing a black suit and bright yellow oilskins, and she must have been a very
striking sight as she stepped onto the pier. Certainly Ewen Ferguson thought
so. He had been waiting to meet his brother, and was totally enchanted by this
beautiful girl appearing out of a miserable day. His initial reaction was ``Oh
what a topper!'' and marked the start of a whirlwind romance and over 30 years
of a very happy marriage.
Ewen was 14 years older than Mary-Flora and had trained as a ship's carpenter
at Brown's on Clydeside. He had started there at age 14 and plied his trade
until the depression of the thirties when he was forced to turn to joinery,
which he didn't enjoy. Just before the beginning of the war he helped to build
the airport at Benbecula and thereafter worked for the council, repairing
schools.
He married Mary-Flora in 1942, and when her younger sister and brother left the
Maclean croft to pursue their careers Ewen and Mary-Flora took it over. He
became a gamekeeper in 1953 and although he got his livelihood from them, he
had no respect for the landlords. He was a great poacher, and as he firmly
believed birds and fish belonged to all men his family ate a very varied diet.
Their daughter Joan was born in 1943, followed by their first son, and then in
1951 they suffered a loss which mirrored Johanna's. Their second daughter Mairi
suffered from a heart defect and lived for only three days, and the anguish of
that time is as fresh for Mary-Flora as it was 40 years ago.
There is still pain in her voice when she quietly says: ``The hardest thing was
coming home with empty arms.''
Although she was very young, Joan can still remember watching the funeral in
total shock and bewilderment. Years later, she too experienced similar pain to
her mother and grandmother when she suffered three miscarriages. None of the
women received any of the special care or counselling available now, but had to
learn to live with their grief.
Another parallel in their lives is that Joan also left school at 15, due to a
very bad bout of appendicitis. However, this in no way hampered her career as,
inspired by an aunt who was a district nurse, she had very clear ambitions. She
is currently a G-grade Practice Nurse, having sailed through a series of exams
giving her qualifications which include District, Family Planning, and
Practical Work Teacher.
As a wife, Mary - Flora undoubtedly worked hard, as at times she supplemented
the family income by working as a cook in what she termed the ``big house''.
However, she also considered herself fortunate her husband had paid employment
and they weren't scratching a living from a croft. When her children were young
her favourite mod con was a stove called the ``Modern Mistress'', which had a
tank at one end so water could be boiled with the minimum of fuss. Likewise,
Joan feels that her childhood was easy, as she didn't have to work on the croft
as she grew up. Culturally they were certainly at a bit of a loss, as there is
a dearth of cinemas and theatres in Uist.
Mary-Flora now lives in Cupar, near her two sons, as does Joan and her husband
Bill Phillips, who was an Officer of Customs and Excise until he retired last
year. The most devastating time of their lives was when they thought they
couldn't have a family, and Joan admits to feeling completely unfulfilled until
they adopted Joanna and then William.
Mary-Flora has ``a lovely wee house and garden'' with central heating and every
comfort she could ask for. Both she and her daughter enjoy their lives, and
despite any heartaches of the past are very content with what they have
achieved. Mary-Flora misses her beloved Ewen who died in 1975, but wistfully
concedes the only price she's paid for a very happy marriage is that she's
``been lonely now for 20 years''.
Grandmother and mother alike are looking forward to next year, when young
Joanna will get married and clearly wish her all the happiness they have had in
their own marriages.
When Joan looks at her daughter and remembers her grandmother, she is very
conscious of the practical changes in the past 100 years. Joanna's education
options and all the choices open to her sum up the generations in this family
and draw a very welcome conclusion. Women may still be fighting for equality
but much of the drudgery has been left behind, providing freedom and
opportunities for Joanna that her great-grandmother could never have imagined.
</TEXT>
