<HEADLINE>Confrontational he may be, but David Trimble scoffs at being branded an unimaginative reactionary The user-friendly unionist</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175686</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINCE no politician cares to be seen standing around for too long, David
Trimble clips through the corridors of Westminster with a marching impatience
to get things done. Of course, ever since the Big Heat of last summer we have
known him to be an effective marcher, the victor of Drumcree, where a multitude
of Orangemen laid siege to a couple of fields for 48 hours while their
delegates quarrelled with the authorities about the right of way.
Even if nothing had been amiss, this was not the best of weather for all those
sombre suits and bowlers as a fiery sun increased the chances of combustion.
Determined to pursue its traditional route into County Antrim's Loyalist
citadel of Portadown, the Orange parade had been halted at Drumcree by the RUC,
intent on preventing any confrontation with a Catholic housing estate nearby.
To the crowd, that instruction was one more sell-out in a year of betrayal, and
into the fray came Trimble, be-ribboned in the manner of an Orange grandee but
holding his peppery temper in check. Abrasive by nature, Trimble has never been
known for mediation but he sensed that this was a defining moment for both
Unionism and his role within it. Adroitly he applied his lawyer's skills and,
after long and sticky negotiations, the march proceeded, but now at 10.30 in
the morning, the Catholic neighbourhood being skirted in an agreed and
unaccustomed silence.
By the time the whole event had ended it was locked in Loyalist folk memory to
endure forever. In commemoration, a Trimble medal was struck but, more
significantly, Drumcree appeared to prove that the MP for Upper Bann was at one
with the rank and file, and within weeks he had been elected to take over James
Molyneaux's stewardship of the Unionist cause. ``I got lumbered,'' he says,
with just the faintest hint of irritation, one small clue perhaps that Trimble
is not the implacable hardliner most suppose.
When the leadership came up, it was his wife who suggested he should put his
name forward as a matter of routine. ``Well, hang on a minute,'' he advised,
``if I do that you realise I might win.'' He downplays personal ambition but
there is no doubt he is pleased by the election's outcome. Yet real regret does
exist that the job now means his young family - four children aged three to 13
- will grow up seeing considerably less of him.
Quick to indignation, Trimble is 51 and although he possesses nothing of Ian
Paisley's booming caricature, it is by his muscular truculence that most of us
recognise him. But offstage, so to speak, his voice has a soothing, almost
whispery calmness as he sits at his Commons desk, appraising the future. Much
has been made of his impatient temperament, and certainly it is true that in a
matter of months he appears to have surpassed Paisley as the most influential
Protestant leading the fight to keep Northern Ireland under British control.
It is obvious, too, that his elevation to the head of the Ulster Unionist Party
shook both London and Dublin where there is a feeling that, under Trimble, the
old No Surrender cry might rise again and add its own particular mischief to
the peace process. But while securing the Union is his stark imperative,
Trimble scoffs at those who would brand him an unimaginative reactionary.
``People are far too narrow in their perception of things,'' he says. ``Of
course I am a Unionist. I am also a liberal Unionist, and a forward-thinking
Unionist. There is no conflict between these three.''
At least, no conflict in his mind, and he is far too clever to cut himself off
from options behind the scenes. But Trimble's scepticism about the actual peace
process has been evident from the start. So, too, has been his anger at
Washington's ``meddling'', although the exasperation seems to have dwindled
since his own ``valuable'' encounter with the White House at the start of the
month. So, if he is low key about the American President's visit to Belfast
this week, the reason is no longer that he thinks it out of line.
In fact Trimble is the only party leader who will be honoured with a one-to-one
meeting with Bill Clinton on Thursday evening. (John Hume will play host to the
President for several hours when he tours Derry earlier in the day, while Sinn
Fein's Gerry Adams, and the Alliance's John Alderdice are expected to meet him
at separate Belfast functions.)
But, in Trimble's view, those who expect the President to make some
progress-on-peace announcement have got it wrong. ``He has to be extremely
careful about this. It's all very well charging into Belfast and declaring, on
November 30, 1995, that peace has regained momentum. But how is that momentum
going to look on November 4, 1996, polling day in the United States. Clinton is
coming to associate himself with peace but the fact is he doesn't want to be
too closely identified now with something which might be a failure in 12
months' time.''
What the administration requires, he says, is nice, warm TV footage of the
President wandering around Ireland, attending functions and meeting people.
``Once he's got that, he will be satisfied. But he will be cautious of
investing presidential prestige in any one political strategy.'' However, even
Trimble's cynicism acknowledges one less facile motive for the hoopla. The
longer violence ceases to threaten, the more public confidence builds in doing
business with Northern Ireland, and this is where Clinton's long weekend will
be most beneficial. ``He is bringing a huge entourage which includes lots of
businessmen, and they are going to see what Belfast now can offer. Believe me,
the contrasts between the worst parts of our city and any US inner urban area
are immense. Indeed, you're a damned sight safer in Belfast than you are in
Washington.''
Trimble's suspicions about the sanctity of the ceasefire are partly conditioned
by the fact that his own security has been increased during the past year. ``I
became aware that I was being actively targeted, and while I don't think there
will be a return to the previous type of IRA campaign I'm very conscious that
if the IRA thinks there are certain people who are obstacles to its plans it
may well try to remove those targets.''
Given those circumstances he professes to see no real point in forging sounder
links with the South, and vehemently opposes the Downing Street/Dublin
Framework for Peace document which refers to cross-border institutions with
executive powers. He believes it is in the South, ``where the IRA has its
base'', that there are people who might indeed wish to kill him, and, anyway,
he has already been to Dublin, he says with the blunt finality of one who
doesn't much care if he never sets foot in the place again.
There are also those who claim David Trimble is profoundly annoyed with Mary
Robinson because he views her various goodwill missions to the North as
usurping the functions of the Queen. It seems he can accommodate the American
President on his home turf, but not the President of the Republic down the
road. Yet ask Trimble what he regards as his character flaws and he admits to
being easily infuriated by people. And his strength? That runs close to being
one and the same: ``I'm argumentative, confrontational.''
Just for a second, though, you wonder if Trimble, in his easy ascents to high
dudgeon, isn't role-playing, for sometimes when he goes into full glare there
is almost a bold irony in that unflinching eye. And take his claim that, to
date, his political career has largely been a chapter of accidents. It is true
he came late to Westminster, after lecturing in law at  Belfast's Queen's
University, where he himself had gained a First. His interest beyond the law
then was current affairs, but by the mid-seventies he was elected to the
Constitutional Convention, although ``I had to be persuaded to do that''.
In 1990 he arrived in the Commons, yet despite enjoying the adversarial nature
of Parliament he says he never really tried hard to get there. ``And now the
leadership of the Unionists - three landmarks but in none of the cases did I
initiate the events. The fact is, once I was in politics I never managed to get
out.''
TRIMBLE'S apparent uncompromising stance on most things hardened during the
seventies when he joined the Vanguard Unionist Party, to the right of the UUP.
Perhaps something of its old fundamentalist zeal stirred in him again when he
emerged in that front line of protest at Drumcree, but the summer siege has not
stopped him from declaring a wish to modify his party's special relationship
with Orangeism which is perceived as having outdated and disproportionate
influence in the UUP's administration and affairs.
``What we are hoping to do is change the way in which the Order appears to be
deeply involved in the internal workings of the party. I say appears because
the reality is otherwise. But we won't turn our backs on our own particular
heritage. I am an Orangeman and I am a Unionist, and I am not going to cease to
be either.''
Still, if Trimble is the radical moderniser he claims, he must dilute the
Orange content of the UUP so as to pursue his pluralist goal of making Unionism
user-friendly to less dogmatic nationalists. One year ago such a notion would
have seemed not merely fanciful but absurd. Even now, with a lifestyle of peace
restored to Northern Ireland, does it make any sense? ``These days most
Catholics are not old-style nationalists. The Republican movement is losing its
coherence, and latest opinion polls show that only 17% of respondents want a
united Ireland. That percentage works out at roughly half the Catholic
population.
``In fact, I believe there is a greater chance of Scotland leaving the Union
than Northern Ireland doing so. You also see old-fashioned nationalism's
decline in the South, where the principal nationalist paper, the Irish Press,
founded by De Valera, has been forced to close because of falling sales.''
But is it realistic to think the UUP could woo John Hume's SDLP voters? ``The
other weekend pollsters asked 100 delegates at the SDLP conference if John Hume
should stand at the next British General Election: 44% said yes; 44% said no,
and presumably the other 12% were undecided.
``What accounts for Hume's popularity among Catholics is that he gave a modern
gloss to nationalism, but when you strip away the rhetoric there is no
difference in objectives between Hume and Eddie McAteer whom he defeated in
1969. The shine is off nationalism, and perhaps that's part of the reason why
so many think Hume should now leave Westminster.''
Trimble warns that the paramilitaries' desire for peace may be a temporary
fling, and he remains anxious that the British Government may fudge the
decommissioning of weapons issue in a frantic bid to revive the talking. ``I'm
prepared to keep an open mind, but I have to say evidence does indicate the
ceasefire is a tactical manoeuvre on the part of Sinn Fein/IRA.
``We know the IRA is continuing to gather information. I'm told by police in my
own constituency that it is still recruiting members, and, on both sides, there
is this business of social control in the form of paramilitary beatings for
those who offend. Since the ceasefire there have been 250 such incidents,
two-thirds by Republicans, one-third by Loyalists.''
Yet in the past 12 months the mood and energy of Northern Ireland's ordinary
folk have been so transformed by momentous optimism even the most unbelieving
cannot fail to be impressed. And Trimble himself has a story which points up
another change. In Glasgow recently he was approached by a man in his thirties
who introduced himself as a Catholic from Derry, now working on the mainland as
an executive for Marks &amp; Spencer.
``He is still a Catholic with a Republican background, but he is now active
within the British economy, and his horizons are no longer the Bogside or even
nationalist Ireland.''
If peace holds out, Trimble's Derry pal may yet find himself back in the North,
with a challenging management future. But maybe that tale's real significance
is this: here was the Unionist's pugnacious champion being greeted by a native
Bogsider. Before the guns and bombs were stilled, who would have dared to
believe in the simple civility of that?
</TEXT>
