<HEADLINE>Let there be byte, minister tells Kirk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175687</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Let there be byte,
minister tells Kirk
A MINISTER has criticised the Church of Scotland for its lack of positive
thinking towards the computer revolution.
``The Church must be there on the Internet to be a positive force for good,''
claims the Rev Iain Morrison, minister at St Ninian's Craigmailen Church,
Linlithgow, in the latest issue of the Kirk's magazine Life and Work.
Mr Morrison, a member of its board of communication, says contacts between the
Church's administrative centres and its congregations have been poor.
Mr Morrison maintains the Internet is the most important communication tool
devised.
``It offers unlimited potential to communicate the gospel throughout the world.
There can, however, be no room for complacency.
``In the past, the Church has been guilty of offering a poor image in its
presentation of the good news, with badly photocopied newsletters and
ineffective posters having been its stock in trade.
``On the Internet, a professional approach is demanded, requiring high-quality
resources to be displayed for the interests of viewers.''
</TEXT>
