<HEADLINE>Capercaillies left homeless as business venture fails</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175688</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE rare Scottish birds face an uncertain future because of the impending
closure of their home.
The capercaillies, renowned for their flamboyant courtship rituals, have lived
in captivity in a Dutch tulip garden in Banffshire for the past four years.
The birds are tame and it is highly unlikely they could survive in the wild.
Their home - The Dutch Flower Bulb Garden at Deskford - is the victim of cold,
wet Scottish springs.
It has failed to cover its costs and the disappointed owner Mr Arnoud Kwint has
returned to Holland.
The birds were hatched from imported Norwegian eggs as part of a breeding
scheme to redress the dwindling numbers of capercaillies.
The birds, two males and three females, have bred 10 chicks this year which
have been successfully introduced to the wild.
Mr Kwint said: ``I have not decided on the future of the birds yet. As they are
tame birds they cannot be released into the wild.''
</TEXT>
