<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Period of calm agreed Cast-iron guarantee for post at Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN, KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175689</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S mail at Christmas was saved last night after the country's 5500
striking postal workers agreed to return to work.
They will begin clearing the huge backlog of 12 million letters and packages.
However, the agreement lasts only until the middle of January and some workers
were predicting further action then if Royal Mail management attempts to force
through changes without full agreement.
The return-to-work decision was taken at meetings in Glasgow and Edinburgh.
Although a large majority voted in favour of a return, it was clear many were
doing so reluctantly.
Last night, some staff were already back on duty, making a start on clearing
the backlog resulting from the dispute which started with a row over a change
in duties at a delivery office in Portobello, Edinburgh.
Plates that had been put over letter boxes by the Royal Mail were being removed
in the wake of the return-to-work decision. It is likely it will take staff,
working overtime, around a week to catch up.
At its height, more than 5500 workers had supported the action, which spread
quickly throughout Scotland. Negotiations between management and unions finally
led to a 14-point peace plan being hammered out.
Mr John Keggie, divisional officer for the Communications Workers' Union for
Scotland and Northern Ireland, said after yesterday's meeting in Edinburgh's
Usher Hall - where workers gave union officials a standing ovation - that
services would be restored as soon as possible.
He declared: ``This dispute was not sought by the union and there won't be any
more disruption or strikes because of the superb agreement we have achieved. We
now have a period of calm where nationally we will look at the underlying
problems.
``We can assure the customers that the experts, not the casuals with the
balaclavas who have been used, will be back on their doorsteps from tomorrow
morning and we also thank the public for their support on this.''
Mr Keggie said the underlying current was that his members feared for their
jobs. The Portobello staff were going back on a set of duties acceptable to
them. The union, he said, had agreed to suspend plans to ballot members on
taking official action against possible job losses and changes in the
deliveries system.
``This back-to-work agreement will resolve outstanding problems, open up
national negotiations, more than likely avoid any further national ballot, and
also deal with back-to-work arrangements as quickly as possible.
``We feel this could all have been avoided. It was unnecessary but hopefully
now we will resolve the long-term problems.''
Mr John Mackay, general manager for Royal Mail Scotland and Northern Ireland,
said: ``I'm dreaming of a good Christmas.''
He rejected as ``absolute rubbish'' any suggesting of humiliation for the Royal
Mail. ``There's no humiliation for anybody in this. We are very pleased good
sense has prevailed and the only winners today are our customers.''
Mr Mackay said the two sides had reached an agreement which meant an immediate
resumption of services as well as a period of calm.
``Both sides have agreed to a UK-wide review of arrangements for provision of
delivery services. A joint approach between Royal Mail and the CWU has been
agreed to look at delivery structures in the Portobello office, the flashpoint.
``We are confident that with renewed flexibility on both sides we will achieve
a staffing structure which delivers the service and efficiency improvements
which our original revised duties were designed to bring about.''
Mr Mackay gave a ``cast-iron'' guarantee that the Christmas post would not
suffer disruption. ``It's our busiest time of the year and we will be pulling
out all the stops as a team.
``We don't want a repeat of last week and we are all fired up to come to a
sensible arrangement for providing delivery services nationally, in Scotland
and in Portobello.''
Asked about disciplinary action arising from the unofficial dispute, he
replied: ``A wonderful job is done by 99.9% of staff. Passions run high at a
time like this with a very few hotheads.''
Any incidents of criminal damage, he said, would be dealt with under normal
Royal Mail disciplinary procedures.
Mr Alan Johnson, CWU joint general secretary, who had flown from London for the
Edinburgh meeting, said the problem was a UK one.
``There is an undercurrent that needs to be resolved and I think the
constructive part about the settlement today is that Royal Mail has agreed
these problems are nationwide. This is just indicative of these problems and we
will now spend six to seven weeks seeking to resolve them so we can guarantee
service to the public.''
Postal workers in Hamilton, Lanarkshire, are still on official strike and
separate talks are being held on their action. The Royal Mail is confident
staff there could return to work tomorrow.
The breakthrough came after the Royal Mail eased its hard-line stance that
staff at the Portobello office had to return and work new duties before further
talks could take place.
</TEXT>
