<HEADLINE>Nuclear convoy doubts raised</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLEGATIONS about the safety of nuclear weapons convoys are to be investigated
by Dumbarton District Council.
It wants to check accident procedures for the convoys, which carry warheads for
Clyde-based submarines.
The move follows a report by two Faslane peace campers who were invited to
attend the first conference under the Government's new ``open doors'' policy on
nuclear issues.
Mr Peter Callaghan and Mr Dave Dragonetti claim that Ministry of Defence
officials admitted local emergency services would be limited in their role and
isolated from the command structure.
Mr Dragonetti said yesterday: ``Snap decisions have to be made in an accident
situation - but this won't happen. They admitted that decisions would be
reached through compromise.
``Quite simply, the armed soldiers travelling with the convoy would throw a
cordon round the spot, nobody would get inside, and the accompanying fire unit
would deal with the needs of the military.''
Among the speakers at the conference in Manchester were Commodore Barry Morgan,
the Defence Ministry's nuclear policy director, Group Captain Ken Proctor, of
RAF Logistics Command, and Mr Ken Johnson, chief scientist at the Atomic
Weapons Establishment.
In their report to the council after the conference, the campers, who both have
tried to halt convoys during demonstrations, warned: ``Local authority
involvement in an accident was not clearly defined. It was not clear what
agency would ultimately take command of an accident situation and how the local
authority would fit into the command structure.''
After a 90-minute question session with the experts, the delegates reported:
``The panel's response was that there would be no overall command, that
decisions would be reached through compromise, and that local authorities would
be informed of the situation as necessary.''
They admitted leaving the conference with the view that the various departments
shared a ``genuine concern'' for the safe transportation of nuclear warheads.
However, they claimed that the experts ``reluctantly'' admitted that fire
services, though skilled, might be limited in their role during an accident.
They also claimed that the experts admitted the huge trucks carrying the
weapons had suffered from faulty braking systems but that the vehicles have
since been overhauled.
The district council is to discuss the claims with the Ministry.
Councillor Jack Duffy said yesterday: ``We are very concerned at the contents
of this report. These matters have been brought to our attention for the first
time.
``We will be seeking assurances from the MoD in connection with safety and
other issues.''
</TEXT>
