<HEADLINE>Cut whisky tax, call to Chancellor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175692</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke was urged yesterday to cut tax on whisky in his
Budget.
The GMB, the largest union in the industry, called for a phased reduction in
tax.
Mr Harry Donaldson, the union's chief negotiator for the industry, wrote to Mr
Clarke condemning last year's extra 26p on a bottle of Scotch as a tax on jobs.
He said: ``UK sales are down by some 2% and the loss in revenue to the Treasury
is also down by about #40m.
``We want you to address the fiscal inequality which is clearly depressing the
performance of an industry so vital to the British economy.''
Mr Donaldson said that the whisky industry supported 14,000 direct jobs, and
50,000 employed in cereals, production, bottling and packaging, transport and
distribution, marketing, advertising and financial services.
``The only solution that will ensure support for this national asset is the
immediate cut on duty as part of a phased reduction of spirit rates cuts so as
to reach an equitable system of alcoholic drinks being taxed according to
alcoholic content,'' he said.
</TEXT>
