<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legal action planned against Eagle Star in #200,000 case after businessman's freak death Firm accused over unpaid policy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175695</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COMPANY chief said yesterday he planned to take legal action against a
leading insurance company which he claimed had reneged on a #200,000 policy for
sales director Gavin Stuart, who died suddenly.
Mr David Munro, head of Unitec Corporation Ltd, in Uddingston, Lanarkshire, had
signed the final papers and payment mandates with Eagle Star for Mr Stuart, a
close friend.
Six days later, Mr Stuart, 41, a father of four, died of a freak illness while
looking after his sick mother at her home in Cathcart, Glasgow.
Mr Stuart, who fell asleep in a chair, died after he inhaled gases from the
gastric juices of his stomach and inhaled his own vomit on August 22.
A week after the funeral, Mr Munro contacted Eagle Star but was told by a
senior executive: ``Sorry, your man was not on cover.''
Mr Munro, 36, said: ``The policy had not been underwritten so, in effect, there
was no cover.''
He said the insurance was a Keyman policy which many top companies take out on
behalf of senior executives who - should they die suddenly - would be difficult
to replace quickly, costing the business thousands of pounds in lost income.
Mr Munro said: ``Gavin's death was a terrible shock to us all. He was an
integral part of our business strategy to develop the business into the next
millennium, including the establishment of an American operation in 1998.
``The insurance was taken out simply for peace of mind. I never, in my worst
nightmares, dreamed I would ever have to call on it. It has been an enormous
personal loss.
``Once we signed everything, Eagle Star's appointed representative told us that
Gavin might need a medical.
``We heard nothing and I expected to start paying the #200-a-month premiums
straight away, because I signed the bank mandates.
``I am not being mercenary when I say I am furious with Eagle Star. They may
have a legal responsibility here - certainly a moral one.
``Would they have started taking the premiums soon after we had signed if
nothing had happened to Gavin?''
Mr Stuart's official starting date with the company was August 21 but he had
already been working as a consultant for four months, prior to starting, at the
multi-media company. It produces videos, software, and training films for
companies including Standard Life and General Accident.
The insurers offered an ex-gratia payment to Mr Stuart's widow Marci, who was
not part of the original insurance plan, and a #5000 ``gesture of goodwill'' to
Unitec.
Mr Munro said: ``I think this is a cynical move to avoid bad publicity. I would
certainly have provided for Marci if the policy had paid out in full straight
away.
``But I refuse to be treated like this by Eagle Star, so I am planning to start
a legal action based on an existing precedent in Scots law.''
Eagle Star spokesman Tony Solomon refused to say how much Mrs Stuart was
offered.
He said: ``These are tragic circumstances. Unfortunately, at the untimely event
of Mr Stuart's death, the underwriting had not taken place and therefore no
contract existed between us.
``He was asked to go for a medical examination as part of our acceptance terms.
It was between that period that he died.
``It is a very tragic set of circumstances and although in law we have no
liability, we have provided a gesture of goodwill to the family.
``Underwriting time depends on how quickly the person taking out the insurance
takes in getting an examination. That is normally a couple of weeks.''
</TEXT>
