<HEADLINE>Irish premier takes initiative with bid to break talks deadlock Bruton in fresh peace moves</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondenta</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175697</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRISH Prime Minister John Bruton last night sent fresh proposals to London in
an attempt to break the deadlocked Northern Ireland peace process.
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams had warned earlier of a return to armed
conflict if the Government refused to set a date for all-party talks.
The move marked the third exchange of documents about the peace initiative
between   Mr Bruton and Mr John Major.
It is believed that Mr Bruton had submitted suggestions for a formula for
compromise on the differences between London and Dublin over Britain's
insistence that there has to be an IRA move towards decommissioning arms before
Sinn Fein allies can enter all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
The latest Irish document came after a London meeting of senior civil servants
from the British and Irish Governments failed on Saturday to make progress
towards settlement of the arms question.
Mr Major and Mr Bruton spoke four times on the telephone about the issue last
week and are expected to be in touch again today.
Mr Bruton sent a settlement plan to London earlier this month and later
received a reply from Downing Street.
Discussions since then have centred on those two sets of proposals and the
Irish Premier's action last night was seen as an intensification of efforts to
resolve the arms impasse.
A Dublin Government spokesman said they were working intensely towards having a
UK-Irish summit meeting at the earliest possible moment.
Downing Street confirmed that the documents had been received from Dublin and
were being studied.
Mr Adams claimed there was no expectation within the British establishment that
any of the armed groups would disarm at this time.
He said: ``None of the armed groups are going to disarm unilaterally or as part
of a precondition. The biggest achievement is the silencing of the guns.''
He said he did not know if the IRA was gearing up for a resumption of violence
and was not in a position to comment on claims that MI5 had warned Mr Major a
ceasefire breakdown was imminent because of the deadlock.
Going back to conflict was inevitable only if an alternative was not found and
the alternative was to talk, Mr Adams told London Weekend's Jonathan Dimbleby
programme.
With President Bill Clinton due in Belfast on Thursday, Mr Adams said the US
administration had accepted, in an even-handed way, Sinn Fein's contribution to
the process. It was not within his gift to persuade the IRA to do anything more
than they had done.
However, Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew said a whole list of
substantial moves had been made by the Government in response to the ceasefire
and people were anxious about the refusal of the paramilitaries even to make a
gesture. What had been asked for was that a start be made to getting rid of
weapons which, it had been conceded, were redundant.
Mr Major sent Mr Bruton an overnight message on Saturday expressing his
disappointment at the impasse.
The possibility of a summit between Major and Bruton ahead of Mr Clinton's
arrival has been effectively ruled out but the Clinton visit may still turn out
to be crucial.
A US administration source was quoted as saying: ``London and Dublin are
important but Northern Ireland is the reason for this trip. This is something
he has wanted to do for a long, long time.''
One report, unconfirmed by Downing Street, which said the programme had still
to be finalised, said Mr Major and Mr Clinton would meet under Belfast's
Christmas tree in a gesture of international support for the peace process.
Senior RUC officers confirmed to the Press Association that there was a strong
possibility the two leaders would meet at the City Hall on Thursday night, when
thousands of people will watch Mr Clinton switch on the Christmas lights. The
two leaders are to have talks at Downing Street before the president travels to
Belfast and Londonderry.
However, Deputy Irish Prime Minister Dick Spring said yesterday that Mr Clinton
was not visiting Ireland with any ``tricks up his sleeve'' about the peace
process.
Mr Spring, who is also Ireland's Foreign Minister, told Irish Radio: ``We are
trying to find a way round the impasse and will continue our efforts. We are
attempting to establish a twin-track procedure, effectively as a means to an
end of establishing all-party talks. There are different opinions held by the
British and Irish Governments and we have to try to overcome those.''
On the Clinton visit, he said: ``I don't think President Clinton has any tricks
up his sleeve. He is not coming in that light and it would be very unfair if
either Government expected him to offer the solution in the context of our
present dilemma. The US want to help but the Irish and British Governments have
to find their way through this themselves.''
</TEXT>
