<HEADLINE>Inquiries after ice rink scare for children</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO inquiries were under way yesterday after 43 people, many of them children,
were taken to hospital after being overcome by ammonia fumes during a junior
ice hockey tournament.
Health and Safety Executive officials launched an inquiry into a leak of
ammonia gas used to freeze the rink at Inverness Ice Centre. Management also
said it was carrying out a full investigation into the incident, which happened
during an under-12 hockey match on Saturday.
Four teams had been taking part - the Comets, Black Hawks, and Tigers, from
Glasgow, and Inverness Spartans.
The leak, which happened just after 5pm, led to more than 200 people, including
players, officials, and parents, being evacuated from the          centre.
Fifteen children and three adults were detained overnight in Raigmore Hospital,
Inverness, suffering from breathing problems, but were released yesterday.
Thirteen of those detained were from the Glasgow area.
Many parents, allocated accommodation in the hospital to allow them to be near
their children, said yesterday they were angry with the evacuation procedures
at the ice centre and demanded a full investigation. One called for the centre
to remain closed until the results of the HSE investigation were made public.
The company, CAC Leisure, initially refused to answer questions over
allegations that ice rink officials had refused to abandon the tournament,
despite repeated warnings about leaking ammonia gas.
But CAC did issue a press statement late yesterday confirming an incident
involving the release of a ``limited quantity'' of ammonia gas from the ice
making plant and that the company was carrying out a full investigation.
It said: ``The escape of gas was mainly confined to the plant room, although a
small amount found its way into the main rink area. The rink was immediately
evacuated in an orderly manner without any public panic.
``The emergency services promptly attended the incident as well as the Health
and Safety Executive.
``Within 90 minutes of the leak being reported, the cause had been identified
and repaired. The ice rink reopened for business from 2pm on November 26.''
A spokesman would not answer any complaints made about the handling of the
matter, saying the company was making no further comment.
During the evacuation, Inverness Spartans' net-minder, John MacLean, 9, from
Maryburgh, near Dingwall, collapsed with breathing difficulties.
His father, Bob, said paramedics successfully revived his son with
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation after he stopped breathing. The youngster, who is
slightly asthmatic, was recovering at home yesterday after being released from
hospital.
He said: ``I felt a tight sensation across my chest and my stomach was sore.
Then I collapsed and the next thing I knew I was in an ambulance.''
Mr MacLean, manager of the Spartans' under-12 side, claimed that rink officials
had seemed ``unconcerned'' after being warned of the gas leak.
``There was no evidence of an evacuation procedure,'' he said. ``The clubs and
first aiders decided to evacuate the teams. But as we were leaving, people
started collapsing. It was frightening. Children were dropping like flies. I
shake when I think about what could have happened.''
Another parent, Mr Hamish Quinn, of Maryburgh, whose son Grant, 8, was detained
overnight in hospital, said: ``This was a most disturbing incident for all the
children. I have never heard of an incident like it before at an ice rink.''
Firefighters carried out an investigation after the building was evacuated.
Inverness Ice Centre, which opened in 1969, still uses a liquid ammonia gas
system to freeze its ice surface, unlike the majority of Scotland's 30 ice
rinks, which now use Arcton, or R22 refrigerant gas. This process too is being
phased out soon because of the presence      of CFCs.
</TEXT>
