<HEADLINE>It's an easy life on football pitch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE standard of Scottish football, currently the cause of anxiety throughout
the game, could be improved by putting players under more stress, a
psychologist claimed yesterday.
Dr Howard Khan, an organisational psychologist at Heriot Watt University in
Edinburgh, and Ms Sarah Hurry, Scotland's top women's table-tennis player,
undertook a nine-month study of the effects of stress on players.
Dr Khan was due to deliver their findings at The British Psychological Society
(Scottish branch) conference in Crieff on Friday but could not attend through
illness.
Questionnaires about stress were distributed to 512 football players in the
Scottish Premier and First Divisions and the results are based on the comments
of 185 players who returned the forms.
They show that players were most stressed by the desire to play well, keep a
place in the team, and get good results for their club. ``Switching off'' from
unfavourable press reports, bad refereeing decisions, and abuse from the crowd
also featured as stressful factors.
However, Dr Khan said Scottish players were not being put under enough stress,
or pressure, and could improve their performance with professional advice.
He said players generally displayed lower stress levels than most of the fans
watching a match.
Dr Khan said: ``Players seem to have a pretty easy life. They train for a
couple of hours every day, play for another couple of hours on Saturdays, and
have a relatively secure job.
``Their performance may improve if they faced increasing demands or their jobs
were less secure. People need to be under pressure to do a reasonable job.
Footballers do not seem to be under enough pressure.''
Dr Khan outlined a series of measures which could revitalise Scottish football
including giving sports psychologists a more active role in helping players and
introducing a ratings system for players and teams to provide achievement
targets.
Players should be given feedback and encouragement.
</TEXT>
