<HEADLINE>Approach to Vatican on Pope's comments</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN COONEY in Dublin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Irish Government is to raise a pre-divorce referendum intervention by the
Pope with the Vatican.
Deputy premier Dick Spring, speaking yesterday after confirmation of the narrow
result in favour of the divorce ban, said he would be speaking soon with the
Papal Nuncio in Dublin.
The Pope angered Irish Ministers promoting divorce reform with his
thinly-veiled ``vote no'' message issued 28 hours before polling day last week.
Talking to Irish Catholic pilgrims in Rome, the pontiff urged ``reflection on
the unbreakable bond of marriage''.
Mr Spring said: ``I will be having some discussions with the new representative
of the Vatican and I am sure that will form part of them.''
Mr Spring added that he did not believe the Pope's comments affected the
outcome of the referendum.
Mr Spring promised early moves to enact the referendum call for divorce in the
light of what he called ``a huge change in social attitudes in Ireland''.
Friday's poll will go down in the history books as the formal ending of an era
in which the Founding Fathers of the Irish State such as Eamon de Valera
colluded with powerful prelates such as Archbishop John Charles McQaid of
Dublin to create a political system whose core values were founded on Catholic
social ethics.
One Vatican expert yesterday compared the result in Ireland as a blow to the
Pope as equal in severity to Lech Walesa's presidential defeat in Poland.
Ruth Wishart - Page 11
</TEXT>
