<HEADLINE>Scot advises on road safety in Syria</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHELL has turned to a Scot for help in cutting the high level of road accidents
among its drivers in Syria.
Safety expert Stewart Wight - the first director of the Scottish Road Safety
Campaign - was approached by the company to produce a 36-page guide for its
Middle East employees.
Entitled Expect the Unexpected - the booklet is intended to reduce the high
accident rate in the wealthy oil state, where there is scant regard for driving
regulations, said Mr Wight.
``It is not uncommon to find a horse and cart coming towards you on the fast
lane of the motorway as the rider makes his way to the quickest exit for his
destination,'' he said.
Mr Wight, 44, who is based in the Grampian village of Laurencekirk, added:
``They have jumped literally from the camel to the car, and powerful modern
cars at that.
``They do not have the knowledge which has evolved to us through decades of
driving and being aware of safety issues.
``They exist on a welter of misconceptions and folklore. One of them is that
you do not leave a space between yourself and the car in front because someone
else will just nick it.
``When I explained that you should just leave a bigger space to compensate,
their logic was that you would end up going backwards.''
Mr Wight has developed a highly successful business based on his road-safety
knowledge and skill in training professional drivers in everything from
anti-kidnap manoeuvres to off-road driving.
The booklet is aimed at British personnel being relocated to Syria but is
already being requested by foreign embassies based there.
``It gives them some knowledge of what they are going to face. They need to
know the problems they are likely to encounter,'' said Mr Wight.
These include no markings around road works, virtually no use of indicators,
animals wandering freely, and tractors sharing the motorways with
top-of-the-range Mercedes cars.
``Indeed, there are so many hazards, Shell has virtually forbidden night-time
driving,'' said Mr Wight.
Syria presently has a highway code consisting of an A3 sheet of paper with
rules on one side and road signs on the other.
``It contains such things as do not drive a car without doors and do not wash
your car in a public place,'' said Mr Wight.
He has high hopes that the Syrian Government, which has become more aware of
road-safety issues since its president's son was killed in a crash, will look
at the possibilities offered by the booklet.
``It could easily be amended to form the basis of a Highway Code,'' claimed Mr
Wight.
His company, Safedrive UK, has previously printed booklets in Arabic, including
one aimed at improving road safety among children. It also operates a mobile
classroom to get the safety message across.
</TEXT>
