<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britain's sinking power on the seas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175703</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Armed Forces no longer have the capacity to launch a Falklands-style
operation, according to a highly classified Government report.
An investigation by experts reporting directly to Defence Secretary Michael
Portillo discovered that Britain no longer has the shipping needed to carry out
an operation on the same scale as in 1982, the Press Association revealed
yesterday.
The crisis is intensified by a delay in orders because of a row over tenders
for two amphibious assault ships each priced at #100m more than expected.
The investigation, by the newly-formed Directorate of Operational Capability,
whose existence is known only to a small group of senior Ministry of Defence
figures, confirmed what Royal Navy chiefs have feared privately for years.
The directorate targeted a number of areas to give Mr Portillo a snapshot of
Britain's ability to meet crises around the world.
The Army's 5 Airborne Brigade and the Royal Marines' 3 Commando Brigade
received the seal of approval.
However, the investigation into amphibious shipping unearthed disturbing proof
that Britain did not have the vessels to respond to a sudden, distant crisis
such as the Falklands, which requires a large-scale naval operation.
The two existing amphibious assault ships, HMS Intrepid and HMS Fearless,
played key roles in the Falklands conflict.
Intrepid is now in mothballs and the Navy has no confidence that the 12,500-ton
ship can even float until trials are carried out and the steam engines fired
up. There is no prospect of trials as there is no money to carry them out.
Fearless is 30 years old and undergoing yet another refit. She remains
steam-driven and has an ageing communications system.
Orders for two replacement ships, which were expected by next month, will be
delayed at least until March because of acrimonious negotiations between the
Ministry of Defence and the sole bidder, VSEL of Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria.
The tenders, #100m more for each ship than the Ministry expected, shocked
contracts staff, who are now trying to beat down the VSEL price.
The sale of the Falklands flagship HMS Hermes to the Indian Navy eventually
forced the Ministry to order a helicopter assault ship.
However, the 20,500-ton HMS Ocean will not enter service until 1997 at the
earliest, after being holed during her launch in October.
The directorate also found that using one of the Navy's three aircraft carriers
as a stop-gap was not a viable alternative as it could only accommodate half
the number of armed commandos and helicopters as HMS Ocean.
The report confirms years of concern among defence experts and merchant seamen
about the scale of the run-down of the British-flagged merchant fleet.
Recently, a number of merchant ships have had to be hired for amphibious
training exercises in Norway.
Despite concerns over amphibious capability, defence sources emphasised that
the current defence of the Falklands was not at risk because the islands'
military infrastructure had been built up.
</TEXT>
