<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots diplomat shot in Kenya</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175705</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH diplomat has been shot in the neck during a high-speed chase in
Kenya as he tried to shake off a gang of car-jackers.
A spokeswoman for the British High Commission in Kenya said Mr Graeme Gibson,
43, from Glasgow, who is second secretary (commercial), had been seriously
wounded in the incident.
Mr Gibson was attacked on the outskirts of the capital Nairobi as he drove home
in his Land Rover Discovery at about 8.30pm on Friday.
A gang in a stolen Peugeot tried to run him off the road but after a chase they
shot him several times, according to the Sunday Nation newspaper.
Mr Gibson was wounded in the neck and lost control of his car which crashed
into a gate.
A police patrol took Mr Gibson to Nairobi Hospital's intensive care unit. The
gang made their getaway after hijacking another car, said police. No arrests
were made.
British High Commissioner Simon Hemans said Mr Gibson, who was driving home
from a commercial reception, took a circuitous route to see whether he was
really being followed.
``They suddenly overtook him, pulled in front of him, one man leapt out and
fired straight at him. Then the car sped off and he was left wounded in his
car,'' he said.
Discovery vehicles were particularly the target of armed hijackers at the
moment, he said. Normally, there was no violence.
``We are still thinking that this was a failed hijack, that the hijackers
thought that they had somehow signalled him to stop, and he hadn't stopped, so
they shot. But he himself is not aware of any signal that he should stop and
hand over his vehicle.''
Mr Hemans said he was concerned for his staff, particularly those with
four-wheel drive vehicles, though the attacks were not restricted to diplomats.
``This is not an anti-foreigner campaign, it's a general phenomenon at the
moment but of course we are concerned.''
He said he had spoken to senior police officers and was satisfied that they
were doing enough.
``They have found the car that the attackers were in when they attacked. It
seems that they had a traffic accident as part of their getaway, and they
abandoned the vehicle, so the police are examining that and are also able to
interview a number of people who witnessed the original attack.''
Mr Gibson has worked in Nairobi in the commission's commercial department since
last November, promoting trading links between Britain and the former East
African colony.
He joined the Foreign Office in 1971 and has also served in several other
African and European countries. He became a second secretary, a middle-ranking
diplomatic position, in 1990.
Twice-married, Mr Gibson's second wife Pamela was at his bedside yesterday. He
has two teenage daughters from his first marriage.
The shooting is the second assault on a diplomat in Nairobi this month. India's
ambassador and his wife were taken to hospital with serious injuries earlier
this month after they were attacked at their home in the exclusive suburb of
Muthaiga, where most diplomats and wealthy businessmen live.
Kenya's Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka said last week that the Government
planned to provide police protection to the homes of diplomats, but gave no
details.
q Last week, businessman Lee Bennett, 46, who left Bradford, west Yorkshire,
for South Africa in 1977, died after he was shot in a raid by three men as he
drove to his house in Johannesburg.
One man fired a gun through the driver's window of Mr Bennett's car. He was hit
in the head and died in hospital next morning without regaining consciousness.
</TEXT>
