<HEADLINE>Brown stands by windfall tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175706</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR said yesterday it would press ahead with plans for a windfall tax on the
privatised utilities despite reports that Chancellor Kenneth Clarke is about to
levy such a tax in tomorrow's Budget.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown said claims that Mr Clarke was about to impose a
one-off #3000m tax on water and power companies exonerated Labour's stand.
The proposal is a key Labour economic policy but it is claimed that Mr Clarke
wants to capitalise on public resentment over ``fat cat'' utility directors. In
a BBC television interview yesterday, Trade President Ian Lang did not deny
that the windfall tax was a possibility but said Mr Clarke would not go for
``cheap, short-term gimmicks'' in his Budget.
Mr Brown said on GMTV's Sunday Programme: ``If Mr Clarke accepts my case, then
this is a further exoneration of the Labour argument, made not just this year
but since 1992, that these profits are excessive and cannot be justified.''
He said it would be an about-turn on the part of the Government, since Mr Major
had described Labour's plan as ``foolish and stupid''.
Mr Brown denied, however, that such a move would shut the door on Labour's
proposals.
``No, I don't think it would,'' he said. ``We will have to look at the
Government's proposals but if the Greenbury Committee on top people's salaries
is anything to go by, the Government never does enough. Anything that is done
is too little, too late. I do not believe that the case for a windfall tax will
disappear after the Budget.''
He confirmed that Labour was considering plans to make another bid to cut VAT
on fuel. Last year, the party defeated the Government on the issue and
prevented a 9.5% VAT increase on gas and electricity bills.
``We are considering that because VAT on fuel is the most unpopular tax we have
seen and we stopped it going up from eight to 17.5%. I would like to see VAT on
fuel go even lower. We cannot get it down to zero but we could get it down to
five per cent and that is one of my long-term objectives.''
Towards the end of last week and again over the weekend, Treasury officials
moved to dampen speculation about substantial tax cuts in the Budget, claiming
there might be just 1p off the basic rate.
This could be accompanied by a rise in tax thresholds to increase incentives
for the lower paid and modest reductions in inheritance tax and capital gains
tax.
However, sources close to the Chancellor have been reported as saying that his
room for manoeuvre is severely limited by spiralling public borrowing.
A limited tax-cutting Budget could disappoint those Tory back benchers who are
pressing for a substantial reduction in the basic rate in what could be the
last Budget before the next General Election.
</TEXT>
