<HEADLINE>MP on way to Pollok</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVAN Labour MP Ian Davidson looks certain to fight Glasgow's new Pollok seat
at the next General Election. Yesterday he won the nomination in two wards
against Councillor Gordon Archer, who was elected to the new city authority
earlier this year.
In Craigton Mr Davidson won by 29 votes to six and in Crookston by 35 votes to
17. The South Pollok ward meets tomorrow. Last night Mr Davidson said:
``Naturally I am delighted the way things are going.''
Drugs seized
POLICE said yesterday that they had made a ``substantial seizure'' of
controlled drugs at an undisclosed address in Dumfries. Two men will appear at
the town's sheriff court today.
Body on beach
THE body of a man was found washed ashore yesterday on a beach at Elie, Fife.
The identity of the man is being withheld until relatives have been informed.
There are not believed to be any suspicious circumstances.
Scots' share
BBC Scotland viewers raised #730,000 for the 16th annual Children in Need
appeal after an evening of televised fund-raising events across the country.
Nationwide the seven-hour television and radio event raised more than #11m,
slightly less than last year.
Ward blaze
POLICE are investigating a fire which broke out shortly before midnight on
Saturday in a ward at Vale of Leven Hospital in Alexandria. Twenty-three
patients were moved to other wards by the four staff on duty before
firefighters arrived. A section of the ward used for medical rehabilitation was
damaged and the hospital said it expected it would reopen within 48 hours.
Police said a patient had been interviewed about the incident.
Heart help
GLASGOW'S Royal Infirmary and Kirkcaldy's Victoria Hospital have each received
#25,000 from the British Heart Foundation. The hospitals are among 19 across
the UK to be given cash in a bid to prevent sudden cardiac deaths. The
foundation said the money would enable hospitals to appoint resuscitation
training officers to teach non-medical staff.
Victim named
A STUDENT who was killed in a road accident in Edinburgh on Friday night was
named by police yesterday as Ms Lorna Wildman, 18, from Strathpeffer,
Ross-shire. She was crossing Potterrow when she was struck by a south-bound
car. Police have appealed for witnesses of the accident.
Pretty penny
CLYDEBANK councillors are spending #150,000 on three superloos equipped with
floor-to-ceiling cleaning systems. The first two will be at Hardgate Cross and
Dumbarton Road, Dalmuir. The third will be built later.
Mine protest
TWENTY-FIVE people protesting against an open-cast coal mine development walked
along threatened rights of way yesterday from Elphinstone, East Lothian, across
the heart of the site on South Elphinstone Farm.
Road death
PAUL Gallagher, 19, has died in Hairmyres Hospital, East Kilbride, after being
knocked down by a car on the East Kilbride Expressway early on Saturday. He
lived in the town's Phoenix Court.
Key questions
AN officer at Parkhurst Jail, Isle of Wight, is at the centre of an
investigation after impressions of keys were found at the top security prison
earlier this month. Police have been informed, but the officer, who denies any
involvement, has not been suspended.
</TEXT>
