<HEADLINE>West adapting to life in prison</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175709</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SERIAL killer Rosemary West is starting to come to terms with having to spend
the rest of her life behind bars, according to a prison source.
The 41-year-old, convicted last week of the killings of 10 young women and
girls, was in a state of shock when taken to Durham Jail on Thursday.
She was devastated as she was placed in her cell in the top security section of
the jail known as ``She Wing'', which houses long-term women prisoners
including Moors murderer Myra Hindley.
According to the source, she spent her first 24 hours sitting on her iron-frame
bed looking blankly at the floor and walls. The source said: ``In that time,
she didn't eat anything, sleep or speak to anyone. It was as if her mind was in
turmoil.''
However, the source said she had since spoken to a prison officer and had
started eating, an indication that she was coming to terms with her situation.
The source dismissed claims that West had struck up a relationship with
Hindley, 51, while on remand awaiting trial.
There have been claims they made unsupervised visits to each other's cells and
prayed together in the prison's chapel, but the source described this as
``absolute rubbish''.
</TEXT>
