<HEADLINE>Women at the helm in march towards the millennium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175710</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a historic first, two women will lead Aberdeen towards the millennium when
the new unitary authority takes control of the city in April.
Mrs Margaret Farquhar, 65, a veteran Labour councillor and the current policy
convener, was expected to become the city's first female Lord Provost, so it
was something of a surprise when Mrs Margaret Smith, 64, who has never
previously held a major position, was elected to the most powerful post on the
new council.
She was chosen by a single vote at the Labour Group's closed-door session,
defeating local political stalwarts Jim Wyness, the present Lord Provost, and
former regional convener Bob Middleton.
Mrs Smith, a former community education worker, is the council's women's and
equal opportunities committee convener, but the two Margarets, Scotland's only
two female council leaders, do not intend to create a women's rights council.
Women's rights will, of course, take its place but they see their role as
trying to provide Aberdeen with the best possible services - without breaching
Scottish Office guidelines.
Indeed they are determined not to give the Scottish Secretary any opportunity
to call the council irresponsible. They are examining whether any cuts are
necessary because of funding reductions but see it is important to explain to
Aberdonians their view that it is Government cuts, not local authority
management, which is causing difficulties.
``I think we will make as good a job of it as any council,'' said Mrs Smith.
``I am encouraged by the co-operation between the councils in looking at the
whole funding problem and realising the cuts are coming from central
Government, and that, in doing our duty to the people of our cities, we are
going to have to make a job of it.
``I think we can. It won't be very easy but I hope we are able to explain to
people what we are doing and why we are doing it in plenty of time so the
citizens of Aberdeen know exactly the position we are in.''
Mrs Farquhar agrees: ``The Secretary of State has cut the budget figures for
Aberdeen and other cities, and we now have to consider whether there will be
cuts and how we can work on the budget we are getting.
``At the end of the day, we have to work on the figures the Scottish Office
give us.
``We have always had a raw deal in Aberdeen but we have always come up trumps
at the end of the day and we will do it again.
``We will behave responsibly and the way we will do that is put the blame
fairly and squarely where it lies and that is with the Scottish Office.
``We are being told time and time again that local authorities are being
irresponsible but before we spend any money, we look very carefully first and
we will continue to do that. That applies on the staffing side, which is often
what is attacked.
``Aberdeen is always seen as a prosperous city and many people are prosperous
but, equally, we have people who are not prosperous. Prices are higher - food
prices, house prices - but we are always totally judged on this prosperity. It
is felt we don't need as much money, we can get it from other sources.''
Mrs Smith said: ``There are a lot of people right on the borderline and new
legislation on benefits will mean even more. We have our fair share of people
who are homeless, people who are very poor, people who are on the breadline.
``Aberdeen has more than its fair share of low pay, particularly for women. The
gap between average earnings and the bottom earnings is enormous.''
The existing district and regional councils have not enjoyed a harmonious
relationship but Mrs Farquhar, who has been involved in discussions over staff
transfers, is encouraged by the early signs.
``I am hoping we can get on together and there are signs that there can be
co-operation,'' she said. ``There will be certain functions which will be
jointly managed by the three councils.''
Mrs Smith said: ``A large number of people came to the consultation meetings,
which showed that people are prepared to turn out and talk about the city they
want to see, from all sections of the community including from the private
sector.''
</TEXT>
