<HEADLINE>Mother to be `given a say' in adoption Mental illness `no bar to her interests'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175711</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE courts have stepped in to protect the legal rights of a severely disturbed
mother whose one-year-old baby is on the verge of being adopted.
Strathclyde region, which wishes to dispense with the 28-year-old woman's
consent to the adoption, objected to someone being appointed to look after the
mother's interests.
However, the Sheriff Principal for Glasgow and Strathkelvin has ruled that the
interests of natural justice demand that the mother should be represented at
any future hearing.
Ms Lynn Welsh, of the Glasgow-based Legal Services Agency, a community law
centre, has been appointed as curator to ensure that the mother's interests are
safeguarded.
She said she regarded the sheriff court decision as ``very significant'': ``If
the region's position were correct, no parent with a mental illness would be
entitled to be protected when action of this kind was being taken.''
The mother was detained under the Mental Health (Scotland) Act the day before
her daughter was born and the baby was immediately taken into care by
Strathclyde's social work department last October.
Earlier this year, the region applied to Glasgow Sheriff Court for an order
freeing the child for adoption.
The court was asked to dispense with the mother's consent on the basis that she
was incapable of giving agreement because of her mental state and also that she
was withholding her consent unreasonably.
The mother, who has a history of psychiatric illness, has been diagnosed as
paranoid schizophrenic with intelligence bordering on mental deficiency.
The baby girl is in foster care and the fosterers have been identified as
potentially suitable adoptive parents.
The mother's consultant psychiatrist became concerned that she was not in a fit
state to instruct lawyers or sign legal documents and expressed his concern to
the LSA.
At a hearing at Glasgow Sheriff Court in June, Miss Irene Henery from the LSA
appeared as a ``friend of the court'' and suggested that the mother's interests
should be represented by a curator.
Strathclyde region objected, but Sheriff I G Pirie decided that the appointment
of a curator was an essential preliminary step before considering the case.
Strathclyde appealed to Sheriff Principal Norman MacLeod QC, arguing that since
adoption proceedings were private, Miss Henery was not entitled to be present.
Miss Henery submitted that the court had a duty to consider the appointment of
a curator because of its concern for people like the mother who might not be
able to represent themselves or instruct a lawyer.
She added that natural justice demanded there should be an inquiry into the
mother's position.
The Sheriff Principal has now issued a ruling that Sheriff Pirie was entirely
justified in deciding to investigate the mother's capacity to agree to the
adoption order.
He declared: ``It is a question that has attached to it considerations of
natural justice. In arriving at his decision the sheriff is going to have to
consider and to weigh in the context of the interests of the child her
severance from her natural mother and, in the context of fairness to the
mother, the question whether proper consideration is being given to her loss of
parental rights and duties.''
Sheriff Principal MacLeod described the region's argument that Miss Henery's
presence at the hearing violated the privacy of adoption as ``unnecessarily
rigid''.
``Miss Henery's presence at the hearing was concerned with considerations of
natural justice and it would be regrettable if, for any reason, the door of the
court were closed in the face of natural justice.''
As far as the appointment of a curator was concerned, the sheriff had the power
at common law to appoint a curator whenever he considered justice demanded it.
The mother was sometimes detained under the Mental Health Act and sometimes
released suggesting that her mental condition fluctuated.
``It seems to me that her interests are of the very kind that a court should be
alert to protect,'' added the Sheriff Principal.
``Miss Henery's purpose in appearing (as a friend of the court) was to express
concern about the protection of a mentally impaired patient, a concern already
shared by the sheriff, and to suggest to the court a course of action that
might meet that concern. Her intervention was simply that of one offering help
to the court.
``It seems to me quite conceivable that in circumstances such as those
presented here, persons in a position to offer help to the court might include,
for example, a mother's parents, a relative, a neighbour or a social worker
independently aware of the mother's circumstances.''
He refused the region's appeal and the case will now go back to Sheriff Pirie
to consider the issue of the adoption.
</TEXT>
