<HEADLINE>Blackmail concern as CCTV video sex footage goes on sale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175712</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPY-ON-THE-WALL video cameras which filmed couples having sex in doorways
yesterday sparked demands from MPs for a Government crackdown.
Their anger follows a row over the sale in video shops of ``juicy bits'' from
closed-circuit TV cameras fixed in high streets and stores to detect crime.
Footage from these cameras is set to go on sale today in the run-up to
Christmas.
One extract shows a couple having sex in a doorway, unaware they were being
watched.
Labour MP Tam Dalyell has written to Home Secretary Michael Howard urging him
to legislate to outlaw the video sales.
``This situation plainly leaves people wide open to blackmail,'' he said.
Mr Dalyell said some of his constituents in Linlithgow had recently been
compromised by such a video.
In his letter to the Home Secretary, Mr Dalyell said: ``Like other MPs, I am
hugely disturbed by what is happening. Films taken for supposedly legitimate
security purposes are being abused for purposes of gratification quite
unrelated to security.
``This brings legitimate video surveillance into disrepute. Do you not think
you should look into this with a view to legislation? At the very least, should
not these films be erased when there is plainly not going to be a security
problem?'' Mr Dalyell added.
Mr Barrie Goulding, maker of the #10.99 video Caught in the Act! said he wanted
to fuel debate about the lack of safeguards on Britain's burgeoning
surveillance industry - by showing just how far he could go in his video.
``It's voyeuristic, I wouldn't deny that,'' he said.
``It is a commercial film and I will make money from it. But there is a message
- who watches the watcher?''
Mr Roger Gale, Conservative MP for Thanet and chairman of the backbench media
committee, said: ``It is essential that the responsible use of closed-circuit
TV (CCTV) as a crime-prevention tool is not undermined by the irresponsible use
of footage showing unwitting and possibly unwilling members of the public in
embarrassing or compromising situations.
``Used properly, CCTV makes a significant contribution to crime prevention and
to seek to make capital out of material gained from these recordings plays
straight into the hands of those who believe that these cameras constitute an
infringement of civil liberties.''
He also urged the Home Office to take steps to prevent any abuse of
closed-circuit surveillance systems.
Liberal Democrat family spokeswoman Diana Maddock said: ``Material caught on
closed-circuit TV must not be used for commercial purposes. That this sale has
been allowed is a disgrace and will undermine the trust the public has in
cameras designed to cut crime.''
She said there was no law prohibiting the sale of these videos although
organisations bidding for #15m of Government money available for CCTV projects
would have to comply with a strict code of practice saying that material must
remain confidential and only for countering crime.
The issue also is being taken up by the pressure group, Liberty, whose
treasurer, Mr John Lyons, said: ``There is nothing wrong with having
closed-circuit TV to protect people and to prevent or detect shoplifting and
other crime but people certainly do not expect to be spied on in this way or
for the material to be sold as entertainment.
``The real danger is that the information could be used by unscrupulous people,
like blackmailers, where, say, an illicit affair is discovered.''
A Home Office spokesman said: ``We have not seen the video but, judging from
what has been said about it, it would have to be classified by the British
Board of Film Classification if it is being sold.''
Mr Goulding said he had thousands of hours of film and planned more releases.
Mr Goulding has courted controversy before with Executions, a film using
footage of actual killings, which he argued was a campaign against capital
punishment. Video stores voluntarily withdrew it after an outcry.
The commentary on Caught in the Act says a low-paid security guard could easily
have been tempted to supply the footage and adds: ``There is nothing to stop
him selling it, us showing it or you watching it.''
Most of the tape shows CCTV performing a valuable service by recording crimes.
Mr Goulding said all the sequences used were supplied ``legitimately'' and that
the identities of innocent people were protected.
</TEXT>
