<HEADLINE>Title flag bound for Bellsland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175713</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DIVISION FOUR
A 58-19 win for Kilmarnock at Haddington, which could have been even more
substantial had six conversions not been missed, sees the Premiership IV flag
destined to be unfurled at Bellsland. With Glasgow Southern slipping up at home
to Ayr by 20-15, Kilmarnock take the title by a clear four points.
With three tries in the opening quarter-of-an-hour, Killie's victory was always
going to be substantial, as was the final try bag of Tony Finnigan - five. Both
Phil Gordon and James Adams grabbed a brace with Stuart Jenkins touching down
once.
Southern played as if accepting the championship was already sewn up. In the
first half, they conceded three penalties, which Ayr's Craig Foster slipped
home. A third success by James Dunlop seemed to have tied the score at the
break but the restart kick brought a penalty and Foster gave Ayr a 12-9 lead.
In the second half, Foster kicked one more to put Ayr 15-9 ahead after 55
minutes. Dunlop's penalties brought the score back to 15-15. But into stoppage
time Ayr's pack rumbled forward for the ball to be whipped blind to centre
Richard Good, who went over.
Gordonians won their home encounter with Langholm by 21-6 to finish third, a
point behind Southern whom they defeated home and away.
Gordonian Kane Barrie and Langholm's Ken Donaldson were ordered off for their
involvement in a mass brawl. Gordonians' Bruce Doney put over seven penalties
from eight attempts.
Edinburgh Wanderers scored 13 tries in beating Wigtownshire 81-3.
</TEXT>
