<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Accies take the plaudits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175714</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DIVISION THREE
THE shape of the top of Premiership III wasn't decided until the final day, but
there was no surprise. Already promoted, Glasgow Accies did the business at
home to Peebles, 37-12, to take the pennant. Biggar finished second, thanks to
a 64-3 win at Corstorphine.
Kirkcaldy kept on Biggar's heels with a 50-12 home win over Musselburgh but
were effectively excluded by last week's defeat at Peebles.
Accies performed as they have of late. An early try, from full back John Mason
with Calum MacGregor converting, was followed by a sag and then a late push.
Terry Greenshields scored a good try for the Borderers to make the half-time
score 7-5. Mike Davis then had two of the second-half tries. Torquil Mathewson
scored once and temporary front-row replacement David McFadzen capped a
two-minute appearance with a touchdown.
MacGregor kicked two more conversions and two penalties. Peebles had the last
word with a penalty try converted by Bell.
Corstorphine go down without a win and their final defeat, at the hands of a
larger Biggar side, was a heavy one. But it could have been worse. With 10
tries scored, usually reliable kicker Dennis Lavery managed only one conversion.
Kirkcaldy's hammering of Musselburgh was revenge for an important early season
slip-up. John Mitchell passed a milestone which few others will even sight.
With 30 points from three tries, six conversions, and a penalty he moved his
points total in league rugby through the 1000 points barrier.
At home, relegated Grangemouth beat Preston Lodge 18-11.
</TEXT>
