<HEADLINE>Labour ready to help in drugs battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175715</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR is set to take up Mr Michael Forsyth's appeal for a ``constructive
approach'' to national issues by presenting him with a 10-point proposal -
including a standing committee of MPs - to tackle the drugs epidemic.
Mr John McFall, the party's Scottish Home Affairs spokesman, has drawn up a
strategy he intends to submit to the Scottish Secretary in an effort to take
the politics out of the fight to stem the drugs trade.
The scale of the problem has become such that he argues an all-party national
strategy is required, and Labour is prepared to co-operate with the Government
to build it. Drugs-related deaths in Glasgow at the weekend brought the annual
death toll to 95.
The measures Labour are considering include the establishment of a permanent
Commons standing committee on drugs that would report to the Scottish Grand
Committee, which is made up of all 72 Scots MPs and is expected to receive
greater powers under reforms due to be announced by Mr Forsyth on Wednesday.
Mr McFall said: ``The scourge of drugs effects the whole of Scottish society
and we have to adopt an approach in the public interest and that means people
working together. Labour is consulting the community and interested parties on
what the best way forward is.
``We think it is essential to take the politics out of this issue. We will seek
all-party consensus for these proposals and will be presenting them to Mr
Forsyth as part of our campaign.''
In a recent interview with The Herald, Mr Forsyth emphasised his desire for ``a
more constructive approach'' to issues in Scottish politics.
Labour proposes to:
q Consult every chief constable in Scotland to improve the co-ordination of
information and policy.
q Seek further legislation to control the use of Tempazepam. Last month, the
Government announced a ban on certain forms of the drug.
q Increase protection for witnesses by improving co-ordination between police
and housing authorities.
q Improve provision of specialist sheltered housing and training for drug users
in rehabilitation. In a significant number of drug-related deaths, homelessness
is sited as a factor.
q New legislation to tighten up laws on shotguns. Under current statutes, a
shotgun owner is not required to obtain further certificates from the chief
constable to own extra shotguns.
The strategy document is reaching its final stages and will be submitted to the
party's policy forming bodies for further consideration. However, the outline
of Mr McFall's proposals are considered ready to be taken forward and he will
seek Government support for them.
q Strathclyde's drug death toll for 1995 rose to 95 at the weekend. Ms Tracy
Mirrlees, 26, of Inchfad Drive, Drumchapel, died in hospital after being
admitted on Friday.
Early reports put last year's total number of drug deaths for the region at 95.
Later figures showed the total for Greater Glasgow was 97.
</TEXT>
