<HEADLINE>Tourists come a cropper</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175717</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUR GAMES
SECOND-half tries by skipper Steve Cottrell and winger Nick Walne earned
Cambridge University a remarkable 22-14 victory over Western Samoa on Saturday.
The tourists, fielding 11 internationalists and eight of the side that drew
15-15 with Scotland, were well below par and never came to terms with
enthusiastic opponents.
Rob Ashforth, the former England Colts full back now playing fly-half, landed
three penalty goals and a long-range drop goal to give Cambridge a 12-9 lead.
Western Samoa had rarely threatened and their points came from two penalty
goals by Cameron Burns and
But, in the second half, the students upped the pace and began to find holes in
the tourists' midfield, scoring two tries, one from New Zealander Cottrell, the
second from Walne.
At last, Western Samoa stirred themselves and five minutes of incessant
pressure, the ball going first to one wing and then the other, led to a try,
which was scored by Patu, but it was too little too late.
q.ALAN McGowan kicked Leinster to a comfortable 15-6 victory over a
disappointing Transvaal side in the first of the South African province's two
games in Ireland at Donnybrook on Saturday.
The fly-half landed five penalties as below-strength Transvaal were made to pay
for a series of errors in a game devoid of tries. Leinster were  6-0 ahead at
the break, and although the tourists got on the scoreboard, McGowan's
consistency clinched victory.
</TEXT>
