<HEADLINE>Rail protest set to spread</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175718</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARIS: Trade union leaders yesterday urged French rail workers to continue
their three-day strike, adding pressure to Prime Minister Alain Juppe over his
unpopular austerity drive. Half the 10 scheduled cross-Channel Eurostar trains
were cancelled yesterday and domestic trains were disrupted in Paris and
elsewhere.
Two leading unions were calling for a general strike tomorrow and students plan
more demonstrations for increased funding on Thursday. Last Friday a nationwide
protest brought Paris and other cities to a standstill.
Skater stabbed
BERLIN: Japanese skater Nami Nemoto was stabbed by a group of six youths in
Berlin yesterday as she was warming up for a World Cup speed skating event.
Nemoto, 20, was jogging outside the Hohenschnhausen rink to warm up for her
3000 metres race when she was attacked, but thick clothing saved her from
serious harm and she was able to compete. Police could not give any motive for
the attack.
Leader sworn in
TBILISI: Former Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze was sworn in as
Georgia's president yesterday and promised to bring peace and prosperity to the
volatile Transcaucasus state. Shevardnadze, 67, who survived an assassination
attempt in August, won 75% of the vote in this month's presidential election.
Coins minted
BEIJING: China's central bank will next month issue one silver and two gold
coins carrying pictures of paramount leader Deng Xiaoping to mark the return of
Hong Kong in 1997.
Gipsy claim
ROME: Police are investigating the case of a nine-year-old gipsy girl who said
a passer-by broke her wrists to punish her because he thought she stole his
wallet. The move comes as Italy plans tough new laws on illegal aliens and the
city of Rome plans to move gipsy communities towards the outskirts.
King in clear
MADRID: Spain's chief prosecutor has dismissed reports linking King Juan Carlos
to two disgraced financiers who allegedly tried to blackmail him over favours
they had provided to the crown. Carlos Granados said he found no evidence of a
blackmail attempt and said the king was not involved in dealings between his
friend and former personal manager Manuel Prado and financier Javier de la Rosa.
</TEXT>
