<HEADLINE>Scientists ready for battle over global warming proof</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PHILIPPE NAUGHTON Geneva, Sunday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175719</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL scientists and government experts are set to agree finally and
formally this week that man-made global warming is already a reality.
The view of hundreds of scientists on the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change (IPCC) is that recent temperature rises cannot be explained away by
natural climatic variations and there is a ``detectable'' human influence on
the world's weather.
However officials fear that the Geneva-based IPCC's ``scientific working
group'', which meets in Madrid tomorrow to finalise its report to governments,
will still come under pressure from energy interest groups to back away from
that conclusion.
``For the first time we're saying that there is human influence on climate, in
the past we've said we're not quite sure - that's a qualitative change,'' said
IPCC executive secretary Narasimhan Sundararaman. ``I don't think people are
going to let that go without a challenge,'' he added.
In their first report in 1990, the IPCC scientists noted a substantial increase
in man-made ``greenhouse gases'' such as carbon dioxide and methane but said it
was too early to say with certainty whether they were responsible for the rise
in average temperatures over the past century.
In the last draft of its new report, the scientific working group notes that
greenhouse gas concentrations are continuing to rise, that recent years have
been the warmest since at least 1860, and that its own ability to predict
climate change through computer modelling has improved.
``Emerging evidence points towards a detectable human influence on climate,''
says the draft report, which will be presented to an inter-governmental
conference of the IPCC in Rome on December 11-15.
Reports on the two other IPCC working groups, on impacts and solutions, have
already leaked out. In them, the IPCC experts predict that as temperature and
sea-levels continue to rise, some small island states could all but disappear,
many of the world's poorest people will see their already arid lands become
deserts, and entire forest types could be wiped out. Floods and droughts will
become more common.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
