<HEADLINE>Boroughmuir drop a point but win friends Disappointment amid a fine feast of rugby</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175720</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Boroughmuir 40, Heriot's 40
THE eyes had it at the end of a pulsating match that produced four tries, four
conversions, four penalties, and 40 points apiece. Bruce Hay and Henry Edwards
looked down at the grass, perhaps sensing that Boroughmuir had now lost their
chance of glory by failing to despatch Heriot's.
And then the sad news came that Iwan Tukalo is to call it a day after the
leagues have finished. ``I've had a great innings,'' said Tukalo, a double try
scorer on the day. ``Yes, I've had my injuries, too, but I don't have any
regrets from my career. There are a lot of young guys putting pressure on me
and I am finding it harder.
``It's sad that we've blown it today. We have blown it haven't we?'' Maybe, but
the two tries, and the instinctive jink from left to right off his left peg
that has been his trademark over the years, were a joy to behold and a reminder
of a great talent that has been around since 1981. Have a great retirement,
Iwan. Same to you, Kenny Milne.
Before the match, a lonely and limping Darren George provided a sad sight for
the home side, and with his injury came the inevitable problem of producing his
kind of possession at the lineout. So, both sides came to Meggetland with
running rugby in mind, and the scores flowed.
First, Teri Rahui and Bryan Easson swopped penalties before a Heriot's attack
swept upfield and Hugh Gilmour swooped in from close range through a ruck of
defenders. It's difficult making your mind up about Hugh Gilmour. He has size,
and fabulous pace, but, like the young Craig Joiner, his aggression seems to
stop in contact.
Joiner grew up on Saturday with a stormer. The realisation that there are few
as strong as him no doubt giving him real confidence coming back from injury,
and Gilmour needs a dose of the same medicine if he isn't to end up as one of
Scotland's greatest ever wastes of talent.
Not content with being 10-3 down, Boroughmuir came back with a try from Tukalo
after Sean Lineen had veered out and given the winger a sniff of the line. A
sniff's enough. What do we make of Lineen then? The best centre playing in
Scotland? Undoubtedly.
Still worth a place in the national team? If he wanted it, yes.
But I rather suspect that he may be thinking of quitting after this season.
``Jeez, it gets harder. I'm too old for this,'' he said afterwards, holding a
pint pot in his hand.
Gilmour retaliated with his second, a long-range one after Stuart Lang had
started it from his own line, David Stoddart made further ground, and Gilmour
roared away from 50 metres. There's the contrast of the man. Absolutely
uncatchable. Lineen replied with a scramble through some dreadful tackling, and
Lang barged over on the line for Heriot's.
So we had arrived at half-time, breathless after five tries, but questioning
whether it had been the great handling, or some slipshod tackling, that had
made the day.
Some good players were having quiet afternoons, notably Stuart Reid and Fergus
Wallace in the 'Muir pack, which had an unconvincing look to it, in spite of
its ability to get the ball back when the backs went up the middle.
An intriguing little duel took place between Graham Beveridge and Fraser
McMillan, two very good scrum halves, and Beveridge will need to learn to be
less obvious in the darker aspects of unsettling his opponent if he is to
escape the wrath of the best refs. That's all I'm saying.
More kicks followed, then the ball was spun left to Tukalo who, yes, came in
off his left foot to dance over. With Easson's conversion it was a staggering
30 points apiece.
A kick each from Rahui and Easson took it to 33, and when a Stuart Reid charge
was halted and a slow maul formed, the ball was popped out to Lineen, who
coasted through an imaginary gap and popped the ball down. Absolutely shocking
defence, frankly.
Would this mean Boroughmuir could still be title contenders? Not if Cameron
Glasgow had his way, and he romped home under the posts to pull the margin to
two points, Rahui's conversion levelling the scores.
It had been a great day's fare for the paying spectators, but there was no
hiding the sense of disappointment in the Boroughmuir camp as they should have
beaten Heriot's but too often lost the ball. There's a lesson there somewhere.
Just before the end, a Boroughmuir replacement came on. ``He's really good
looking isn't he,'' said the journalist beside me. Luckily, she was a girl.
Times are changing.
Boroughmuir - N Mardon; A McLean, D Laird, S Lineen, I Tukalo; B Easson, G
Beveridge; G Wilson, N Dickson, L Graham, A Cadzow, D Burns, F Wallace, S Reid,
J McKinlay.
Heriot's - S Lang; C Glasgow, D Stoddart, G Lawrie, H Gilmour; T Rahui, F
McMillan; M Livingstone, K Milne, S Paul, P Young, S Gilmour, S Elliot, T
McVie, G Dall.
Referee - R Megson (Edinburgh Wanderers).
SCORERS: Boroughmuir - Lineen, 2t; Tukalo, 2t; Easson, 4c, 4p. Heriot's -
Gilmour, 2t; Lang, 1t; Glasgow, 1t; Rahui, 4c, 4p.
</TEXT>
