<TEXT>
ISRAELI authorities may have needlessly kept hundreds of Holocaust survivors in
psychiatric hospitals for nearly half a century, health officials admitted
today.
Dr Motti Mark, head of the Health Ministry's mental health department, said 900
people - nearly one-fifth of Israel's institutionalised mental patients - were
Holocaust survivors.
Most, he said, arrived without families in the late 1940s and were immediately
taken to hospital. With more sophisticated treatment, he admitted, some might
have been able to begin normal lives.
The disclosure followed a report on Israeli television which alleged systematic
negligence for decades in dealing with the trauma of some immigrants who
arrived after surviving the Second World War slaughter of millions of Jews.
``It definitely did not have to be like this,'' said Mark. ``These people came
to Israel alone and got help, but when the treatment ended there was nobody
outside to receive and support them . . . We, Israeli society, did not become
their families.''
q Israeli police are interrogating at least two rabbis suspected of issuing a
religious ruling that justified the killing of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
Assassin Yigal Amir reportedly believed Rabin was under such a ruling because
of his policy of turning over land to the Palestinians. The rabbis could be
charged with inciting murder.-AP.
</TEXT>
