<HEADLINE>Padre shows `Minister' the way home in Fighting Fifth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175722</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHIEF Minister just failed to land a gamble at Newcastle on Saturday, coming
late in the Fighting Fifth Hurdle but just failing to catch Padre Mio.
The bookmakers were well pleased that Tom Dyer's Chief Minister finished
second, as many punters had plunged heavily on the 15-8 favourite.
``He ran to his best form and might have won given another 100 yards,'' said
the Tayside trainer.
Chief Minister may not have won yet this season, but his recent third at
Cheltenham and Saturday's second place, earned a total of #11,000.
q.COULDNT Be Better produced a fine display of jumping to land the Hennessy
Gold Cup after One Man's chances of running were washed away by heavy rain.
The winner was well ridden by understudy Dean Gallagher to secure the #50,000
prize, the most important success so far for either jockey or trainer Charlie
Brooks.
Couldnt Be Better's task was made easier by One Man and Young Hustler's
defection.
``I've been so close in so many big races. To ride in and win the Hennessy is a
dream come true,'' said Gallagher.
q.JODAMI, Cheltenham Gold Cup winner in 1993, is assured of a tremendous
welcome at Kelso today when he runs in the Hinchliffe Champion Chase.
Peter Beaumont's 10-year-old was to have run in the Hennessy, but was withdrawn
because of the threat of firm ground and having to take on One Man, who beat
him at Ayr two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
