<HEADLINE>Parachute bombs kill 37 in Kabul</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175723</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REBEL jets bombed residential areas of Kabul today, killing at least 37 people
and wounding more than 140 in the heaviest air raid on the besieged Afghan
capital in more than a year.
A Defence Ministry spokesman blamed rebel Islamic Taleban militia, who seek to
topple President Burhanuddin Rabbani, for the attack. At least nine bombs were
dropped by SU-22 planes, none hitting a military target, he said.
A ministry statement also accused neighbouring Pakistan of responsibility,
saying it had ``strong evidence'' indicating Islamabad's technical and
financial aid in repairing the SU-type jets Taleban seized from the western
town of Herat in August.
Pakistan rejected the charge. ``This is utter nonsense,'' said a Foreign
Ministry spokesman in Islamabad.
An Afghan Defence Ministry spokesman said the Taleban used three SU-22 bombers
in the air raid, making two passes over the city 15 minutes apart.
At least 12 people died when one bomb destroyed three homes and severely
damaged four others in the western suburb of Wazir Abad. Neighbours said the
device was a 1100lb parachute bomb that exploded in the air above the suburb.
The parachute bombs are designed to explode about 90ft above ground, spraying
their target with shrapnel.
A similar bomb killed seven people in a three-storey mud-brick building, where
neighbours said three families were living. Rescuers dug frantically through
the rubble but found only corpses, including the bodies of two infants.
``This is the most barbaric war,'' cried one neighbour as he watched the
rescuers cover a two-year-old child dragged from the dust. ``The Taleban are
more cruel than Ghengis Khan. Even the Russians were not as bad as these
people.''
``This bombing is the biggest crime,'' said another resident, Najim Khan. ``God
will not forgive those who committed this.''
Doctors in Kabul's four main hospitals said they treated about 150 bomb
victims, eight of whom died later, bringing the death toll to 37. The air raid
followed two nights of heavy fighting between the Taleban and government
fighters.
A Western analyst said the air attack could be a response to recent Taleban
setbacks, although it was hard to see any military logic in the raid.
The Taleban is attacking Kabul on at least four fronts in a bid to capture the
city and force Rabbani from power. It has also imposed an energy blockade on
Kabul in an apparent attempt to freeze the defenders into submission over the
coming winter.
The Taleban has rejected UN proposals for a multi-party council to replace the
government and has pledged to occupy Kabul by force.
-Reuter.
</TEXT>
