<HEADLINE>Rebels repeat hostage threat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175724</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE shadowy militant group holding four Westerners in Kashmir today repeated
its threat to kill them if India did not meet their demands as soon as possible.
An Indian Government official said: ``They warned that if government does not
concede their demands as soon as possible they will execute four Western
tourists.''
Indian Government negotiators made contact with the Al-Faran militant group
today after a gap of three days.
``Government representatives had meaningful talks with Al-Faran this afternoon
and hopefully talks will continue,'' said K B Jandial, a spokesman for the
government of Jammu and Kashmir.
Britons Keith Mangan and Paul Wells, American Donald Hutchings, and German Dirk
Hasert were kidnapped by Al-Faran guerrillas in July. A fourth captive,
American John Childs escaped. A fifth, Norwegian Hans Christian Ostroe, was
found beheaded in a remote Kashmiri forest on August 13.
Al-Faran, unknown before the kidnappings, has demanded the release of 15 jailed
separatists, including three Pakistanis from the Harkat-ul-Ansar militant
group, in return for freeing the hostages.
India has refused to bow to the militants' demands and has ruled out a rescue
raid for fear of endangering the hostages' lives.
Authorities say they believe the four tourists are unharmed and their captors
might be considering releasing them.
``This is just pressure tactics, hopes for the captives' freedom are high,''
said an official.
The hostages have been sighted from time to time, as their abductors lead them
through isolated villages.
Kashmir, India's only Muslim-majority state, is torn by a five-year separatist
rebellion in which more than 20,000 people have died.-Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
