<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What price loyalty?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175727</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO that's the leagues nearly over, and the big question is: What's going to
happen to loyalty now, then?
Keeping up to date with all of the machinations is like trying to catch the
bits of an exploding hand grenade as they fly here and there.
``What happens now?'' folk often ask.
Something to do with regional leagues, and cup, and a few other things, I think.
I think that the players will use everything at their disposal to weed out the
best deal from the SRU, but I can't help thinking that the reason some of our
big boys aren't doing so well is because all of this money chat is diverting
attention away from the core skills of rugby.
To heck with the players earning some dosh, the important bit is that the clubs
survive and, as I survey the leagues, I ask myself: What on earth has happened
to Stew-Mel? They are down. And one of the ramifications of a club like that
going down is, unless they can stop their demise, then they are on a downward
spiral. It seems just like yesterday the club had its Calders, Scotts, and
Brewsters. All of whom made up one of the best club sides in the land.
Alan Kittle has left, Graeme Burns, their scrum half, is on his way to Saracens
in England, Ross McNulty is going to Currie, and No.8 Dave Clark is considering
a move to Boroughmuir. All of which will remove more players from the staff at
the club, and ask questions of director of rugby Finlay Calder as the club
slips into the third division.
He blames the lack of regard for club loyalty. ``I think club loyalty is going.
Players will give their current club one season, but, at the end of that, any
loyalty will be stretched in the current climate,'' said Calder. ``I believe in
the traditional values, and I think it's wrong to leave.''
Who can argue with Calder? Players are going to start shifting in their droves
now, as they do in football.
And Calder, who has long been an advocate of giving the clubs their place at
the head of rugby's table instead of districts, goes further than that to say
that too many clubs in Edinburgh vying for the top spot is bad for the game.
``I wouldn't mind if some of the stronger clubs merged to form very big
clubs,'' he said. ``But you have to say that the present set-up is too tight.
``I accept that the success or failure of our side has been down to 15 men on
the pitch, but we have been playing to avoid relegation since the start of the
season. Eight teams and two down is just too tight.''
As for the suggestion that he might now take the easy route and take his leave
from his club, he scoffs.
``Stewart's Melville are part of my life. It's part of my family. I can't just
turn my back,'' said Calder. ``If I am asked to go on then I will.
``Our lack of success hasn't been down to bad coaching, or a lack of kit, or
anything like that.
``The players have been well looked after. Nervousness has crept in. If all
five of our teams had been getting beaten then I would be terribly deflated and
things wouldn't have been working, but our seconds beat their Stirling County
counterparts on Saturday and they really shouldn't have.''
Calder cites his game against Kelso on Saturday - he came on after five minutes
- as proof that club rugby has to be the way ahead for the game, despite all
that has been said after the Western Samoan game.
``I can't get excited by district rugby,'' said Calder. ``On Saturday, Kelso
had their biggest crowd for years. The people appeared because they wanted to
tell the players that the club meant something to them. Clubs are the
foundation of the game, but the structure of the season has placed a noose
around our necks. It is just too tight.''
He has a point, and it has been aired many a time by others. But it's a good
one about club loyalty.
One of the end results of placing district rugby ahead of club rugby - and they
say the SRU players' contract has a clause about bonus payments for playing
district rugby - is that clubs, without stretching the point, will become
places of convenience for aspiring players to play and be seen. Just as they
are in football.
You are loyal to the man who pays you the most. And where that takes us, God
only knows.
</TEXT>
