<HEADLINE>Mediterranean nations seek free trade zone</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175728</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE European Union and a dozen Mediterranean countries haggled today over the
details of a political and economic alliance aimed at creating a free trade
zone by 2010.
Diplomats debated arms control and terrorism issues to be included in a joint
statement the foreign ministers of the 15 EU and 12 Mediterranean nations will
issue on Tuesday.
The two-day Ministers' conference starting in Barcelona tomorrow will launch
the EU's most ambitious bid to date to improve relations with countries on its
volatile southern doorstep, from Morocco to Turkey.
``Tomorrow begins a new chapter in relations between Europe and the
Mediterranean nations,'' said Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana, who will
chair the 27-nation conference.
It is seen as a bid by the West Europeans to become more assertive in a region
where it has long played second fiddle to the United States.
The EU is offering #4000m in aid over five years to its 12 partners: Algeria,
Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria, Tunisia, Turkey,
and the Palestinian Authority.
Libya has been excluded because EU nations consider it a sponsor of terrorism.
The EU wants to stop the flow of illegal immigrants from North Africa and
stifle Islamic fundamentalism around the Mediterranean that is seen to threaten
Western Europe's security.
Diplomats tonight tried to reconcile different interpretations of
``terrorism'', with Syria and Lebanon insisting it must not be confused with a
people's right to use violence to gain freedom.-AP.
Barcelona, Sunday
</TEXT>
