<HEADLINE>Meningitis student an isolated case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175729</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 18-year-old Scots university student who was taken to hospital on Thursday
suffering from meningitis, remains in a critical but stable condition.
Forth Valley Health Board yesterday insisted the case of Mr Christopher Scott,
a first-year student at Stirling University, was isolated.
A spokesman sought to reassure the public by saying that friends who had come
into contact with the student had all been traced and given treatment.
Mr Scott, who is understood to come from Falkirk, remained in the intensive
care unit at Stirling Royal Infirmary yesterday. He became ill on Thursday and
was taken to hospital, where his condition deteriorated.
The latest news of the student's illness has been confirmed amid growing
concern south of the Border where health officials say they have identified
five separate clusters of meningitis outbreaks since October.
As an immunisation programme got under way on Saturday in Lincoln, where five
people have died and two are still seriously ill from the disease, the Public
Health Laboratory Service confirmed meningitis had also appeared in
Worcestershire, Warwickshire, Norfolk, and Sussex. Health officials said there
had also been individual cases, including one in Liverpool.
Dr Andrew Riley, consultant in public health medicine with Forth Valley Health
Board, said yesterday the case of Mr Scott was isolated and there was no
connection with any other cases as far as health officials had established.
Last week, after consultation with public health officials, Professor Andrew
Millar, Principal of Stirling University, sent a statement to all 2000 students
residing in campus accommodation.
The principal said the symptoms to look for were flu-like with severe headaches.
He urged students who believed they might be at risk to contact their GP or the
porter or security at the university on 01786 467000.
</TEXT>
