<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serbian nerve gas plants exposed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175730</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TERRIFYING new threat to the prospects of a lasting peace in the Balkans is
exposed with the discovery that Serbia has factories capable of making deadly
nerve gases.
World In Action claims it uncovered proof that the former Yugoslavia was
producing the nerve gas sarin and assisted Saddam Hussein by helping build
Iraq's main chemical weapons plant at Samarra. The Yugoslavs also developed the
Orkan multiple rocket launcher for Saddam to deliver the lethal gases,
according to the programme.
Former US Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger says international sanctions
on Serbia should not have been lifted until the Serbs gave an ``absolute
assurance'' that they would scrap their chemical weapons.
Major David Craig, chemical warfare adviser to General Sir Peter de la
Billiere's in the Gulf War, went to an abandoned nerve gas factory between
Muslim and Bosnian Serb front lines north of Mostar.
Analysis of samples from the plant confirmed that sarin had been produced there.
Major Craig said: ``What you have discovered is that Yugoslavia was producing
weapons of mass destruction and that the Serbs still have the capability to do
so.''
Former staff in the top-secret nerve gas programme describe the capability and
locations of several factories in Serbia which can still make sarin.
Secret Yugoslav army documents and manuals detail Serbia's preparedness to wage
a chemical war.
Former Yugoslav President Stipe Mesic explains how he made a secret trip to the
United States to brief the Pentagon on the threat posed by his own army's
collaboration with Saddam.
Although he was head of state, his trip had to be kept secret from his own
forces and he used a ``private'' visit to Austria to board an American jet for
his clandestine trip to Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nuclear `guinea pigs' await ruling by European Court</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175731</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EX-SERVICEMEN who were used as human guinea pigs in the 1950s will learn this
week if they have won a 12-year fight for compensation.
The British Nuclear Test Veterans' Association, which is pressing for a #2000m
award from the Government, claims its members have suffered cancers and other
life-threatening diseases from radiation exposure.
More than 22,000 servicemen, many of them Scots, witnessed the Pacific bomb
testing programmes between 1952 and 1958. Many subsequently died or are in ill
health.
The European Court of Human Rights this week will consider three cases - all
involving Scots - during a two-day sitting due to start tomorrow, with a final
ruling expected on Thursday.
The move will bring an end to a 12-year struggle started by Renfrew Councillor
Ken McGinley, a former Royal Engineer who was sent to Christmas Island in 1958
and witnessed six explosions.
When Mr McGinley, 57, and his colleagues started their fight for compensation
in 1983, the group from Johnstone, Renfrewshire, alone numbered 11. Since then,
five, all of whom had cancer-related illness, have died.
Of his time on Christmas Island, Mr McGinley said last night: ``We were ordered
to face an explosion with fists firmly clenched and pressed into our eye
sockets. I was wearing a white boiler suit.
``Some of the men said that when the heat and light hit us, they could make out
the bones in their hands, like an X-Ray.
``The heat was so intense that I felt it burning my bones and, a couple of days
after, I broke out in a bad skin rash.''
Mr McGinley, who is adamant that there has been a massive cover-up, said the
European Court's decision was the ex-servicemen's last hope of a victory.
Mr McGinley has also suffered from medical problems since his involvement in
the tests but he is not allowed to discuss them for legal reasons.
He said: ``This is not just a fight for the veterans but for the widows and the
dependents, sons and daughters, who have been affected.''
The British Nuclear Tests Veterans' Association has 3000 members throughout
Britain and they are being represented by Paisley-born lawyer Ian Anderson, now
a leading New York attorney, through public donations and financial aid from
sympathetic local authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctors urge end to records trade</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175732</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTORS have demanded action to stop the secret trade in personal medical
records by private detective agencies.
Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell was urged to launch an inquiry into the
disclosure that confidential health files can easily be bought from High Street
agencies for #150.
Doctors want to see the leaking of medical records made a criminal offence and
a general rule imposed that any NHS employee who breaches patient
confidentiality is sacked on the spot.
The scale of the problem was revealed by a Sunday newspaper which gained
permission from a number of politicians and other influential figures to obtain
their medical records.
Dr Sandy Macara, chairman of the British Medical Association, was one of those
who took part in the exercise.
He was shocked by the ease with which his confidential records were bought from
a detective agency for #150. The information was faxed to the newspaper within
three hours of the order.
In a statement yesterday, Dr Macara said: ``I am appalled that the media has
been able to obtain my personal medical details but I'm not at all surprised.
``The BMA, supported by all the health professions, has been demanding adequate
protection for the confidentiality of identifiable personal health information
for several years. But we have been unable to persuade Ministers that there is
any cause for concern.''
One year ago, the BMA published a first draft of its own proposals for a law
making the unauthorised divulging of medical records a criminal offence.
The idea was rejected by the Government but the BMA hopes to gain backing for a
revised version of the Bill.
The spokesman said new European rules on health confidentiality due to come
into force by 1998 would eventually compel the Government to support such
legislation.
Fears about confidentiality have been further heightened by plans to link
computers in an information network covering the whole NHS.
</TEXT>
