<HEADLINE>MP murdered on campaign trail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From OLEG SHCHEDROV Moscow, Sunday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175733</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RUSSIAN MP was murdered today on a campaign trip for next month's General
Election, prompting an outcry over the government's failure to stop crime.
Sergei Markidonov was shot in the head and a bodyguard received head wounds
while campaigning in the eastern Siberian town of Petrovsk-Zabaikalsky, about
3000 miles from Moscow.
Early reports by Russian radio suggested the bodyguard had shot Markidonov,
possibly after a row in a hotel room, and tried to kill himself.
``After killing the deputy, the bodyguard tried to commit suicide,'' the radio
said. ``He was found in a serious condition at the scene of the crime by local
police and taken to hospital.''
Markidonov, a liberal, was the fourth MP from the State Duma to be killed since
the last election in December 1993. The other deaths were linked to an upsurge
in gang murders and violent business rivalries.
Markidonov was elected to the Duma in 1993 for the reformist Russia's Choice
party. He later crossed to the pro-government group Stability.
The Communist Party quickly denounced the authorities.
``No matter how Markidonov was killed, the whole thing has a touch of
politics,'' said senior party member Viktor Ilyushin. ``Our grief has a great
deal of regret about the complete impotence of the bodies created to fight
crime in the country.''
q The Communists are confident of achieving a spectacular comeback in the
Russian elections on December 17.
Opinion polls show that the successor to the party which ruled with an iron
grip for more than 70 years could win most seats in the Duma.
Communists and nationalists, riding a wave of discontent over market reforms,
look set for a sizeable share of votes at the expense of the liberals.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
