<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sarajevo `will be new Beirut run by Nato' Bosnian Serb leader claims capital `is going to bleed for decades'o</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From SEAN MAGUIRE Sarajevo, Sunday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175734</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN Serb leader Radovan Karadzic warned today that Sarajevo would become
the Beirut of Europe if the city was reunified as laid down under the Dayton
peace plan.
However the Bosnian Government derided his words as scaremongering and said the
Bosnian Serb army was to blame for the city's predicament because of its siege
and bombardment of Sarajevo for more than 3!s years.
Karadzic spoke on British television from his headquarters in Pale outside
Sarajevo as part of a growing Serb campaign of opposition to parts of the peace
plan initialled on Tuesday in Dayton, Ohio. Diplomats say the Serb moves augur
badly for the chances of its complete implementation.
However the chief US negotiator for the Balkans, Richard Holbrooke, ruled out
altering the accord to suit the Serbs. He told US television today that there
would be no change when it is formally signed in Paris next month.
The Bosnian Serbs are incensed that Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic,
negotiating on their behalf, agreed to Serb-held Sarajevo suburbs reverting to
Bosnian Government control.
``Bosnian Serbs in the city of Sarajevo . . . will require special status,''
Karadzic said, calling for changes in the plan.
``What is wrong with the Dayton agreement is that it has created a new Beirut
in Europe. It is going to bleed for decades,'' said Karadzic, playing to
Western fears that Nato troops will become bogged down in further fighting in
Bosnia.
Beirut was divided by a Green Line battle zone into warring halves during the
brutal 15-year civil war which wrecked the Lebanese capital in the 1980s.
A Bosnian Government official dismissed Karadzic's predictions that reunifying
the city would lead to disastrous intercommunal fighting, saying Sarajevo was
never ethnically divided before the war.
``Karadzic was fighting for four years to make Sarajevo look like Berlin before
the wall there came down,'' said Bosnian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mirza
Hajric.
``The peace plan means that terrible dream has not come. But since Karadzic
couldn't create Berlin he'll do everything in his power to create a Beirut,''
he said.
Karadzic repeated a call first made on Serb television on Friday for at least
five years of international protection for civilians in Serb-held suburbs.
``Serbs in Sarajevo have their own rights and their own fears,'' said Karadzic.
``They are not willing to accept Muslim authority.''
Diplomats said that if Nato troops ``protected'' Serb civilians in the way
Karadzic wanted, their presence would simply bulwark the Serb hold on areas
around the capital which they do not want to give up.
Belgrade analysts said Karadzic's provocative comments came of desperation, as
he had been cut out of the Dayton talks by Milosevic.
The Bosnian Government says human rights guarantees, and its pledge not to
victimise Serbs who opt to stay in areas that fall to its control, should
satisfy the concerns of Bosnian Serbs, who have begun to demonstrate against
the peace deal.
Karadzic mixed conciliation with defiance in his interview, pledging to accept
the overall peace plan but declaring open rejection of clauses that bar him
from staying in power.
``I am the legal and legitimate representative of my people . . . I did not
issue any single wrong order or decision,'' he said, denying that he was guilty
of war crimes.
NEW YORK: Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said that the US and Europe should
work more closely to end wars such as that in the former Yugoslavia.
``One of the lessons we should learn is that the United States and Western
Europe should decide jointly from the very beginning what their common course
of action should be,'' he told Newsweek International.
Citing difficulties with decision-making when the US became involved in the air
in Bosnia, he said: ``Either we should all be there on the ground or no-one
is.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
