<HEADLINE>Cricket fans die in stadium collapse</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175735</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nagpur, Sunday
AT LEAST nine cricket fans were killed and 50 injured when a stadium wall gave
way today as crowds were leaving for lunch during a one-day international
between India and New Zealand.
Part of the back wall on the eastern stand at the Vidarbha Cricket Association
(VCA) Stadium collapsed as spectators were making their way out.
``At one moment I saw the wall, in the next I saw several people falling
down,'' said journalist Joseph Rao.
Three spectators, including a 23-year-old woman, were killed immediately and
another six died in hospital, police said. At least 14 of the injured were in
serious condition.
Witnesses said a 10ft wide section of the brick wall appeared to give way in
the crush of people trying to leave the top level of the stand.
Some victims fell over the edge as the wall collapsed, plunging 50ft to the
ground, while others were hit by debris.
More than 100 people had been perched on the wall.
The cricket club announced it would pay 50,000 rupees (#1000) compensation to
the families of each of the dead.
The match, the fifth one-day international between India and New Zealand in the
Kiwis' current tour, continued despite the tragedy. New Zealand beat India by
99 runs.
``There would have been a riot if we had suspended play,'' said a VCA official.
The stadium is to host one of the world cup cricket matches, between Australia
and Zimbabwe, on March 1. The eastern stand had only recently been
completed.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
