<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mose Allison, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rob Adams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175739</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE uncharitable viewpoint might be that Mose Allison is a know-all. Advice? He
gives it. For naive country folks moving to the big city, he's got the lowdown.
For those who just don't know when to stop, he's got the red light. For the
writer of You Are My Sunshine, he's got the inside track on how it was really
meant to scan.
Coming from a different source, all this agony uncleship might get a mite
tiresome. But not coming from a man who, with heavy self-disparagement, sings
of sitting there in his cowboy suit, lookin' cute, who admits that one of these
days he's gonna get things straight, and whose version of Sunshine makes you
think, damnit, he's got a point.
A man so disposed towards giving advice might also take some: play solo. His
piano playing, with its quaint digressions into Monkish baroque, wasn't best
served by a rhythm team forced to rehearse some fairly fussy moves as they
went. Neither was his naturally light singing, although his own instructions to
the sound engineer (who thankfully knew better and gradually undid the wrong)
didn't help.
Allison is anyway a performer best suited to the most intimate of settings. His
quick-thinking hipster word play demands closer concentration than this
restive, not to say impolite, audience allowed. But distractions aside, his
blend of jazz sophistication and his native Mississippi blues, taking in Nat
King Cole and Muddy Waters songs, together with a ready wit, make for one of
the most entertaining and idiosyncratic talents around.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>County cannot believe they let this one slip. Borderers smash and grab the draw</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175740</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stirling County 15, Melrose 15
JUST about the only thing left cut and dried after this riveting clash between
these two championship contenders was Brian Edwards' scalp.
The Stirling County coach was sporting what in the tonsorial trade is termed a
``No.1 all-over.'' Edwards declined to go into detail but it was, he divulged,
a legacy of the celebrations which followed his North and Midlands boys'
victory over Western Samoa.
A win for Melrose on Saturday would have placed them in pole position for a
championship-settling outing against Gala on Saturday. The draw now means that
a victory against their near neighbours next weekend, in their final
championship outing, will place them on 19 points.
County, however, are currently on 15 points with two games to play. The
Bridgehaugh men meet Boroughmuir on Saturday, and Heriot's the weekend after.
They, too, have the potential to finish on 19 points.
Currently, Melrose are 41 points to the good on scoring differential and it may
yet come down to that.
The scenario of another batch of drawn games next weekend underlines how this
eight-team premiership has turned into a mathematician's nightmare and was not
at all what the spin-doctor ordered.
The most immediate concern for Stirling, though, is just how they contrived to
let a 15-point lead dribble away into the sand and especially so when it is
considered that for most of the time that they were those 15 points to the good
they were more than worth that lead.
County had Melrose under the cosh for almost the entire first half. Mark
McKenzie missed three kickable penalty goals inside the first quarter of an
hour and, inexplicably, chose to run another well within range to no avail
after 30 minutes, and, had these chances been turned into points, then we may
well have witnessed an entirely different ball game.
Let us, though, take nothing away from Melrose. They got their lineout working
in the second half - Weir plucking some choice balls from the ether - and Craig
Chalmers banged down some telling positional punts which kept County on the
turn.
Craig Joiner on the Melrose right wing, recovered from the foot injury which
has kept him out of the premiership since September, had one of those ``great
to be back'' days. He had a try but that was the least of it. The sustained
power of his running was the thing that most caught the eye.
Joiner had the hex on his international team-mate, Kenny Logan, the County
left-wing experiencing one of those ``I wish I was anywhere else but here''
days.
The exuberant Logan's loss of form is a concern, certainly for County but
equally for the national selectors. Good players don't become bad players
overnight. Some remedial work might be in order but both County and Scotland
need Logan firing on all cylinders.
County appeared to have taken the lead after six minutes when Colin MacRobert,
displaying electrifying pace, skinned Gary Parker on the outside and stormed in
for a ``try'' which was disallowed after the touch-judge Jim Johnston flagged
for some unnecessary footwork by Bob Cairney on Rowen Shepherd.
Stirling did take the lead after 23 minutes after the nervousness which
pervaded Melrose's first-half effort manifested itself in a defensive guddle by
Shepherd and Bain. Logan swooped on the scrap ball, fed Davie Elliot - the
under-rated mystery man of Scottish back-rows, said Edwards - who set Gareth
Flockhart off on a 50-metre dash for the line. McKenzie converted and, at last,
County had something to show for their efforts.
Ten minutes later, Ian Jardine, who was beginning to capture the form which
made him a pre-injury mainstay for Scotland last season, scored a timely try
after severe Stirling pressure but in the closing minutes of the first period
Melrose began to grab a semblance of the control which set them up in the
second half.
It was, though, first blood to Stirling after the interval with a McKenzie
penalty goal but, thereafter, they never troubled the scorers again.
Craig Chalmers began the resurrection shuffle with a sparkling try which Parker
converted.
Then Joiner had his try as Melrose continued to prove the dominant force, and
Parker kicked the equalising penalty goal 10 minutes from the end.
It was a real pressure kick, the more so as Parker - like McKenzie - had not
experienced the best of afternoons with the boot, but the ball flew true and
Melrose take their championship aspirations down to the wire.
Teams:
Stirling County - C M Sangster; C C MacRobert, I C Jardine, M N McGrandles, K M
Logan; M McKenzie, K G M Harper; J J Manson, R Cairney, G B Robertson, J S
Hamilton, M Norval, D Elliot, G N Flockhart, B Ireland.
Melrose - R J S Shepherd; C A Joiner, D C Bain, A G Shiel, G A Parker; C M
Chalmers, B W Redpath; M G Browne, S J Brotherstone, D Lunn, R R Brown, E M
Simpson, S A Aitken, G W Weir, I Feaunati. Replacement I Cornwall for Lunn
(23min.).
Referee - J Fleming (Boroughmuir).
SCORERS: Stirling County - Jardine, 1t; Flockhart, 1t; McKenzie, 1c, 1pg.
Melrose - Chalmers, 1t; Joiner, 1t; Parker, 1c, 1pg.
</TEXT>
