<HEADLINE>Cappella Nova, Glasgow Cathedral</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175741</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST in case there is anyone out there who hasn't heard yet, 1995 is the
tercentenary of the death of English composer Henry Purcell. While Radio 3 is
broadcasting in the year every extant piece he ever wrote, more than a few
local music organisations have also marked the occasion.
On Saturday evening it was the turn of Cappella Nova to add their contribution,
seeking to give a Scottish dimension by focusing on Purcell's sacred and
secular music composed during the reign of the last Stuart king, James II and
VII.
Whatever the excuse for revisiting Purcell, his sacred music transcends the
merely temporal and in the opening anthem the voices of Cappella Nova soared
towards a celestial plain. This kind of piece exemplifies the group's
extraordinary power to sublimate individual voices to a greater overall unity,
in this case Purcell's intended heavenly harmonies.
For the rest of the anthems the choir was augmented by the chamber group,
Concerto Caledonia, who provided instrumental introductions as well as the
continuo. Their generally light, delicate playing provided a sensitive balance,
underscoring rather than overwhelming the vocal lines. Where solos were called
for, such was the high quality of performance throughout that it would be
unfair to mention individuals other than to remark on the superbly rich and
powerful basses.
Not so satisfying was Welcome Song for James II, the secular work which closed
the concert. A less measured direction by Alan Tavener, with a little
decoration here and there, might have yielded a more expressive result.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000061</DOCNO>
