<HEADLINE>Cartoons better value on Saturday</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175742</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVING travelled all the way from the sticks of West Aberdeenshire, and paid
#38 to support Scottish Rugby and watch that abysmal performance on Saturday
afternoon, my wife and I feel we have been cheated.
Any more of that type of entertainment, and there will be two debentures on the
open market to the biggest bidder, and I shall seek better value from watching
Tom &amp; Jerry on the TV.
The only entertainment we got was the commitment of the Samoans to run the ball
forward and their dance of appreciation at the termination of the match.
What did John Beattie write in your journal last week? ``He hoped, Oh how
forlorn, he hoped we would see some entertaining running rugby from the
Scottish team,'' and what did we get?
A fusilade of misguided kicks from our ``stand off,'' who, in June, was
described by a Scottish scribe as one of the great tacticians of the game. That
was in a World scenario you know.
The arrogance of some of those who wore our National Colours is beyond
comprehension. They are so unfit it is unbelievable. To put in a performance
such as that, how can they ask for and command a fee, let alone a jersey?
A number of players came out with credit, but they were few. Oh, and John
Beattie, don't run away and hide, you are the only guy in the game scene who is
speaking some sense, and that includes the hierachy of the SRU.
F G Lawson,
F G Lawson &amp; Sons,
Asloun,
Alford.
</TEXT>
