<DOCID>GH951127-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Cheers' to the end of boos</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175743</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOYAL supporter that I am, I joined those thousands of other good Scots rugby
enthusiasts at Murrayfield for my forty-eighth year of indulgence in this
pilgrimage.
I am obliged to conform to the new rules of ``not even a hip flask for
medicinal purposes,'' and I can accept the need for this ruling.
However, I cannot accept the whistles, yells, and bugles that erupt from a
considerable percentage of the Scottish supporters on the occasion of the
visitors penalty conversion attempts.
Why, why has this crept in over the past few years? It is hardly noticeable at
the other Five Nations' grounds.
I honestly want to cover my face in shame when this happens. I was delighted to
hear the SRU's tannoyed plea to cease this foul practice on Saturday.
Who are the culprits? Could that army of stewards searching for the
middle-aged, grey-haired businessman having a fly sook at his flask secreted
behind his moth-eaten sporran, not be better employed pinpointing the whistlers
or howlers from the schoolboy ranks?
What are the guardian teachers or school-masters doing about it?
Come on Scotland. Let's play the game. We can ``stand against them'' without
this disgraceful display of unsportsmanlike bad manners.
Stuart Cordner (Sr),
Shore Cottage,
Tarbet.
</TEXT>
