<HEADLINE>Christie's quartet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175744</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT SEEMS little changes in men's indoor hockey, on the evidence of play on the
first weekend of the new season at the Bell's Sports Centre in Perth. With the
standard of play and umpiring continuing to drop, Menzieshill and MIM remain
the leading sides in the country and John Christie is by far the top
personality.
Christie, the Scottish internationalist, proved his worth to Menzieshill, the
defending champions, scoring four of their goals in their 5-1 defeat of
archrivals MIM.
Officials have clearly become alarmed about the deteriorating quality of play
but until such time as there is a break between the indoor and outdoor season,
little will change. The plight of the umpires wasn't helped by the cancelling
of the pre-season briefing meeting, particularly with some new umpires coming
into the game.
Insights Inverleith gifted equalisers in their two matches yesterday on the
final hooter against Torbrex Wanderers and Grange.
Their biggest embarrassment came in their tussle with Grange. Four minutes were
remaining in the match when Derek Batchelor elected to introduce Norman McLeod
as a kicking back in an attempt to eliminate Insights' 3-0 lead. The tactical
move worked, with Colin Pretty, Andy McBride, and Gary Boomer all scoring.
</TEXT>
