<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clarke must get sums right for leadership</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Geoffrey Parkhouse</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>inside politics</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175745</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR 25 years Kenneth Clarke has been marked out as a Tory leader to come. As a
newcomer to the Commons in 1970 the plaudit used to both please and irritate
him. Teased about it, he used to say: ``Thanks a million - I now join the long
list of Tories who fail to become party leader.''
It was still fashionable in those days to camouflage one's brilliance if one
wanted to get on. He worked at his natural bloke's temperament, his man's man
nature. Football, beer, jazz, cheap cigars, crumpled suits, suede shoes.
Tomorrow Kenneth Clarke will not mind a bit if, having delivered his Budget,
people start marking him out again as the next leader. It will indicate this
man of the world has given the Tories a fresh chance of retaining power. This
could make him the heir apparent whether Major wins or loses.
In short, the Chancellor could be back in the frame if he gets his judgments
right. Over the last two years or so he has not found favour in the right of
his party, despite his description of himself as coming from ``the hard
centre''.
It is five years since he told Margaret Thatcher she should bow out gracefully
before she was thrown out by the parliamentary party, but the Thatcherites'
grudge is still there. He is thought to be soft on Europe, refusing to denounce
outright a single currency, and that is another score against him on the right.
At the same time his views on abortion and capital punishment are too liberal
for them.
Coincidentally, as long as Michael Heseltine was a possibility for leadership,
support for Clarke was muted. Now Heseltine appears to have committed himself
totally to Major as his Deputy, Clarke could be poised as the best man to lead
the reviving One Nation concept of Conservatism. Tomorrow is a watershed for
his prospects and those of the Government.
At 55, he has more than sufficient experience for the top job. A Cabinet
minister for 10 years, he has been involved in trade and industry, and
employment. Before becoming Chancellor two years ago, he was Home Secretary,
Education Secretary and Health Secretary. For Margaret Thatcher he took on the
doctors, nurses, firefighters, police, and teachers in a series of bruising
encounters over pay and conditions.
When he was confronting the ambulancemen, perhaps the most rancorous of his
disputes, a petition of 4.5 million people was delivered against him. By
October 1990, he was the Cabinet's low man in an ICM poll with a 60%
disapproval rating and only 18% aprroving his deeds. This was despite the fact
he secured an additional #2.6 billion for the NHS from the Treasury in
November, 1989.
Norman Tebbit thought highly of him in those days, describing him as ``vigorous
and combative'', a future Tory leader, ``getting on with things I would like to
see done''.
Two years later, in October 1992, the then Chief Whip, Richard Ryder, had to
seperate the two men as they were about to come to blows at Lord Jeffrey
Archer's conference party. They were arguing about Maastricht, and Clarke (who
had been accused of not reading the Treaty) told Tebbit: ``You have declared
war on the Government; we have no choice but to take you on.''
This was unusual for Clarke who normally laughs his way out of this kind of
trouble and remains, as his wife Gillian says, ``impossibly calm''. But he
likes to give as good as he gets and Tebbit fights rough. Major and his whole
Government were being destabilised by the Tory Eurosceptics at the time. The
following year, Major appointed Clarke as his Chancellor, replacing Norman
Lamont.
He had been part of the Black Wednesday emergency Cabinet team and had seen the
pound demolished and the decisions to raise interest rates twice in one day to
15%. Still, as Chancellor, he refused to rule out the possibility Britain
should return to the European Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM) one day.
``Our membership (of the ERM) certainly helped us to achieve the low level of
inflation which is one of the best bases for making industry competitive as we
move into the recovery,'' he said.
``The five-point reductions in interest rates before we left the ERM were as
valuable as the four additional point reductions we have made since we left the
ERM.''
By this time all but the Europhiles in the party were of the opinion the Tories
would gain by coming right out against the ERM for ever. Some saw it as being
used by the likes of Clarke at a future date to ease us into a single currency.
But Mr Major was not prepared to rule out the ERM for ever and, as Clarke told
the Tory conference in October 1993, ``Any enemy of John Major is an enemy of
mine''.
This was the year that he introduced a Budget with the biggest increases in
taxation and the toughest restraints on public spending since the Second World
War. Tory taxation has increased by seven pence in the pound and the party's
reward is to find itself at its lowest-ever ebb in public opinion.
Clarke states his political philosophy is ``free market economics combined with
enlightened social reform'', much as Mr Major might say. There is no doubt this
Cambridge Law graduate and former QC has the intellect to cope with his immense
task. His oratory skills are better displayed at the Despatch Box than on a
platform; his administrative record is patchy, but civil servants who have
worked for him give him the benefit of any doubt. He is now a shrewd politician.
He has the common touch. One pacifist grandfather sold the Daily Herald at
trade union rallies; the other, a Raleigh bicycle toolroom engineer, was a
Communist. He is named after his father - an artisan who sent him to Nottingham
High School before Cambridge where he became President of the Union and, some
say, the brightest of the ``mafia of Tory politicians'' who made it to Cabinet
rank.
All the attributes for leadership are in place. Tomorrow he has the chance,
perhaps his last, to use them to get the Tories out of the mess they are in.
</TEXT>
