<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother Courage and her Children, Royal National Theatre, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Dillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175746</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE action of Mother Courage and her Children in its current revival at the
National Theatre is preceded by a giant crow circling above the stage. The crow
returns to haunt her at each change of scene. Somebody must have decided that
an audience raised on TV commercials would be unable to comprehend a play about
the waste and depredation of war without a hefty visual nudge to ram the point
home.
It's a shame because such false notes are rare in Jonathan Kent's
well-considered production. For the most part we're given a welcome reminder of
the power of Brecht's kind of theatre. The scope is huge, the versatility
breathtaking.
Songs, settings, and language work together to build up the overall effect.
Even the smallest role in this large company is finely characterised. This is
theatre of epic ambition achieved through mastery of detail. Jonathan Kent,
well served by David Hare's lively new translation, refuses to shirk the play's
many ambiguities. Mother Courage is both indomitable and cowardly; we find her
superb even while we shrink from her cynicism.
Diana Rigg, in the title role, eschews histrionics in favour of a performance
carefully judged to fit in with the whole company. We are not asked to pay
homage to a great actress at work. Instead she achieves her effect by a wealth
of well-observed detail. Rigg reveals every side of the role and we are left at
the end devastated as much by her laughter as by the fate of her children.
For some reason Brecht has gathered a reputation for heaviness on the British
stage. Any doubts on this score will be removed by this lively and imaginative
revival.
</TEXT>
