<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Divorce can offer mixed blessings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ruth Wishart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175747</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WISDOM and politicians are not always the most obvious bedfellows. However, the
Irish Premier, John Bruton, discarded triumphalism for compassionate
commonsense when the campaign to permit divorce, which he had supported,
squeaked home at the weekend.
Bruton insisted the result should not end in acrimony since he believed both
Yes and No voters were only about 60% convinced of their decision.
That was a wise, shrewd, and almost certainy accurate observation. Like all the
pieces of legal Elastoplast we attempt to apply to wounds in the human
condition, divorce is an imperfect healing mechanism. Many people who changed
their vote from last time will still harbour genuine fears about the impact on
Irish family life.
And many still persuaded to vote No will have personal knowledge of loveless,
violent unions in which partners have been trapped until death do them part.
Nevertheless, I believe Ireland was right to take the difficult step it did,
not least because in a modern multi-cultural society, one whose citizens
embrace several faiths and none, it should not be the business of any one
church to blackmail the State.
Nor should it be the business of an elderly, celibate, unmarried male Polish
Pontiff to dictate to the men and women of Ireland how they should conduct
their personal relationships.
It is even being supposed this morning that his intervention in the debate
pushed many waverers into the Yes camp; if so, it is a neat form of secular
retaliation.
Nevertheless, while the availability of divorce in Irish society should be a
cause for quiet celebration, not least for those second families who will now
be able to enjoy a formal blessing if they so wish, nobody should suppose the
act of legal separation is without serious consequences.
Undoubtedly, there will be many thousands of men and women in Ireland for whom
the possibility of divorce represents a long overdue escape from the dire
domestic consequences of a disastrous union. But there will be those who are in
the midst of one of those negative patches familiar to all married couples who
would be foolish to suppose a trip to the courts is a surefire recipe for
instant sunshine.
Marriage, sharing your entire life with one other human being, could be said to
be a triumph of optimism over logic. But the fact so many divorcees seem
hell-bent on giving it another whirl, regrettably with less chance of success
than before, suggests most of us still believe in its potential for emotional
satisfaction.
However, there is another consideration more important than the immediate needs
of the adults concerned in a failing relationship, and that is the long-term
interests of the children. In their recent report on childhood, Barnardo's
reflected on the fact the post war generation had managed to convince
themselves a civilised divorce was better for children than a battle-scarred
marriage.
Barnardo's concluded that assumption to be badly flawed - more of a useful
alibi for parents than a sustainable analysis. The uncomfortable reality for
parents contemplating separation is almost all the evidence suggests the
reverse . . . children whose parents break up are more likely to have a range
of problems than those whose parents stay together.
An examination of the background reports on children who go through the
Childrens Panel system, or young adults who find themselves in court, will
provide a depressingly similar picture of disrupted childhood. Equally,the
statistics on homeless or abused children or those who become victims of street
violence will contain a disproportionate number of young people who have spent
many of their formative years in care.
The more we research this subject as a society, the more it become absolutely
clear the best chance we give children is as stable and loving a childhood as
is possible to deliver; inevitably that will often mean the best interests of
the children being given priority over the personal inclinations of the adults.
None of which is to argue adults should be obliged to tolerate any kind of
distress or abuse in order to keep the domestic show on the road. At the
extreme end of the spectrum you have instances such as Fred and Rosemary West,
both of whom came from households littered with violence and sexual abuse.
Households where that kind of monstrous rewriting of the rules of civilised
behaviour has gone on are not households in which you want to maintain the
status quo for the children. Nor should women be expected to tolerate routine
and drunken violence as the price of maintaining a two-parent home.
There will be many people in Ireland who have had to do just that with little
hope until now of a legal settlement which would afford them justice and the
means to embark on a financially independent lifestyle.
However, there are other kinds of marital breakdown, less dramatic and not
involving violence or abuse. Relationships where people become indifferent
rather than hostile, bored rather than battered - marriages where that boredom
leads to affairs or semi-separate existences. Where there are children involved
it seems to me you need a better excuse than the absence of bliss to throw
their vital years into emotional disarray.
It's absolutely no accident the army of therapists now plying their trade on
this side of the Atlantic as well as the other go about their business by
having their clients try to identify, confront and then deal with difficulties
they faced with family relationships when they were young - that is the period
when the seeds of success or otherwise for all future relationships are sown.
It's absolutely no accident children whose parents separated are less likely to
suppose partners living together for a lifetime is a sustainable option.
Ireland is lucky in the sense its long debate over law reform has allowed it to
witness how the rest of the world has handled the reality of broken marriages.
If it has learned anything it will be that while divorce affords certain
freedoms, it rarely comes with solutions attached and always implies casualties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
