<HEADLINE>Facts and an outraged figure in call to order</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175748</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Beattie suggests that, in liaising with the Western Samoan authorities to
that country's tour to Scotland, I telephoned them in the middle of their
night. A light-hearted quip in his Diary piece it may have been, but a quite
outrageous and damaging accusation to make without checking facts first.
The SRU's policy in dealing with overseas Unions is to contact them at times
which are convenient to them - and, therefore, sometimes at great inconvenience
to us. As a courtesy to a visiting country, it meant that telephone calls made
by me to Western Samoa were made in the middle of our night.
John Beattie, as a columnist and former player, is entitled to express his
sometimes trenchant views. However, he should have had the courtesy of first
checking his facts with the SRU.
I A L Hogg,
Secretary,
Scottish Rugby Union plc,
Murrayfield,
Edinburgh.
q.The ``outrageous and damaging'' accusation to which Mr Hogg refers, was in
fact contained in an after-dinner speech by the Western Samoan manager, the Rev
Dr Faitala Talapusi, at the post-match banquet. The reference was light-hearted
in intent, and did not detract from a fulsome tribute to the SRU for the manner
in which they had hosted the Samoans. Similarly, as Mr Hogg notes, the diary
item was a ``light-hearted quip'' and in no way intended as a slight on the SRU
secretary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
