<HEADLINE>Flyers grounded</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIGEL DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175749</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIFE Flyers' player-coach Mark Morrison aimed to build on the encouragement of
pocketing three points out of a possible four from their last two games but his
hopes of moving up the premier division table were dashed at the weekend.
Flyers were put to the sword 13-3 by Sheffield Steelers last night, a far cry
from their encouraging recent Benson and Hedges Cup semi-final clash with the
Yorkshiremen, who were forced into extra time after the sides were level at 8-8
after two closely-fought legs.
Sheffield won through to Saturday's final with a quick strike in sudden-death
over-time.
Last night it was a different story as Sheffield dominated the three periods,
winning the first 2-0, the second 9-2, and the third 2-1.
On Saturday, Flyers' weekend got off to a bad start when they were caught cold
by Basingstoke and never recov-ered. They lost the first period 4-1 to the
former league leaders, and went down 7-3. Results:
Saturday: Premier division - Basingstoke 7, Fife 3; Milton Keynes 3, Sheffield
3; Nottingham 4, Cardiff 2; Slough 6, Humberside 11. Division 1 - Bracknell 19,
Billingham 0; Dumfries 4, Medway 3; Paisley 6, Blackburn 7; Swindon 10,
Manchester 6; Telford 12, Murrayfield 4.
