<HEADLINE>For Gala, pride comes before a fall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175750</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gala 24, Hawick 23
IN the Gala committee room afterwards, I was bold enough to suggest that this
had been a terrific game of rugby, the kind to win supporters back to the
terraces and great fun for all concerned.
``Aye,'' came the immediate response from a worthy. ``I suppose it was grand if
you were a neutral.'' They have been battling with each other since 1876, after
all.
No matter that Gala appear doomed to demotion next term - although the latest
reconstruction rumour suggests we might have a 12 team First Division - this
was the Border Old Firm and pride is always more valuable than points. There
were Grants and Suddons and Patersons about and most of them have been fighting
since Flodden.
Gala should have won by the length of the High Street. Throughout the game,
their forwards, inspired by John Amos, who has been a light in the darkness all
season, sent back enough ball to win a championship.
Their backs, though, were not so slick and actually contrived to present two
tries to the opposition. Hawick could hardly believe they were back in the
match - then almost win it right at the death.
There was a wee bit of history made at half-time. When John Graham went off
hurt, on came Grant Harris for the Greens. This is the lad who has been
reinstated following a spell in rugby league with Carlisle. I cannot recall
such a happening in this fixture before. May it be the first of many.
Scott Welsh kicked the opening penalty for the visitors but Gavin Dalgleish
soon equalised that and added a second for good measure.
Robert Hogg knocked down a lineout ball to Tom Weir, who galloped away for a
Gala try of which brother Doddie would have been proud. Dalgleish converted and
added a penalty goal.
With the interval looming, Scott Paterson, an enterprising full back, joined
the line, Amos was there, too, and they made a try for Chris Dalgleish.
Hawick heads were hanging and fell even lower when Gavin Dalgleish put over
another goal. Welsh reduced the deficit with a penalty before Keith Suddon
pounced for the first of his two tries.
A breakdown in a Gala handling movement gave him the chance and when he was
gifted an interception and raced the length of the field for his second, he
must have checked the date on the calendar. Welsh converted the first, Colin
Turnbull the second.
Turnbull's next penalty cut the margin to a single point and the last quarter
was frenetic. Weir was almost over, so was David Liddle for Gala, but Jim Hay
took a vital strike against the head then very nearly grabbed to winner.
Referee Eddie Murray kept good control and his final whistle was greeted with
much joy. Among those celebrating was the Gala debutant Brian Laidlaw, son of
Scotland and British Lions hooker Frank.
Kent his faither.
Gala - S W Paterson; M Moncrieff, E Andrew, M Stumbles, C S Dalgleish; G S
Dalgleish, D A Paterson; G R Isaac, I Corcoran, H A Hunter, D T Weir, R B Hogg,
B Laidlaw, D R Liddle, J P Amos.
Hawick - C W Turnbull; G W J Sharp, C A Murray, D S Grant, K L Suddon; W S
Welsh, K W Reid; M Russell, J A Hay, B J McDonnell, A Barnes, I Elliot, J
Graham, B L Renwick, G L Allott. Replacements - G Harris for Graham
(half-time), D Gordon for Welsh (53min.), F Jack for Murray (65).
Referee - E Murray (Greenock Wanderers).
SCORERS: Gala - G Dalgleish, 4p, 1c; C Dalgleish, 1t; Hogg 1t. Hawick - Welsh,
2p, 1c; Suddon, 2t; Turnbull, 1p, 1c.
q GLASGOW have lost John Lonergan for the inter-district championship programme
next month. The 32-year-old West of Scotland No.8, who has played three games
for Glasgow, most recently in the 21-7 win over Griqualand West last month, is
unavailable because of business commitments.
Lonergan's West colleague, David Barrett, had previously declared himself
unavailable. So had Stuart Simmers, Glasgow Academicals' scrum half and
captain. To those three losses can be added two Stirling County players, Mark
McKenzie and Brian Robertson, who have opted to switch from Glasgow to North
and Midlands this season.
Glasgow's team is expected to be named early next week for their opening match
in the district championship, against North and Midlands on Wednesday week, at
Beveridge Park, Kirkcaldy.
</TEXT>
