<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gallacher stays on course for card</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Matthew Lindsay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175751</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Stephen Gallacher departed for the European Tour Qualifying School in Spain
last week his uncle Bernard offered him some wise words. ``Don't try and win
the thing, just try and get your card,'' was the Ryder Cup captain's advice.
Though he has adopted a sensible approach in Spain this week, the 21-year-old
nevertheless trails the commanding leader, Thomas Buhrmann, by just four
strokes entering the critical final two rounds, having posted a three-under-par
69 across the harder San Roque course on the Costa del Sol yesterday.
With a stiff wind buffeting competitors the youngster's round was the lowest of
the day as scores soared into the high 80s. Gallacher played superbly and
recorded five birdies and only two bogeys.
The severity of playing conditions was best illustrated in the exploits of
Jeremy Robinson, a European Tour player for some seven seasons. Entering
yesterday's play at one-over-par he was comfortably positioned to make the
four-round cut, but crashed out dramatically with a 15-over-par 87.
Excellent putting on slick surfaces has been the key to the Scot's success this
week, although he revealed that some slight swing changes had brought an upturn
in fortunes.
``I noticed that I was coming over the ball slightly at the point of impact, so
I worked hard on the practice ground. I struck the ball superbly today,'' he
explained.
Raymond Russell of Longniddry posted a similar score, carding four bogeys, two
double bogeys and four birdies, including a sub-par score at the demanding
final hole. The 23-year-old fired a No.6 iron to the water-guarded green and
calmy rolled home a 20-foot putt.
``That left a nice taste but overall I am extremely frustrated, said Russell.
`` I am playing well but not scoring well. It has been the same story every
day, so hopefully soon something will happen.''
Sadly, the only other Scots to join that pair in the final two rounds are Scott
Henderson of King's Links and William Guy of Buchanan Castle. Leading
aggregates:
277 - H Burhmann (S Africa) 67, 73, 69, 68.
281 - S Gallacher (Scotland) 72, 72, 68, 69; M Wills (Wales) 71, 68, 70, 72.
282 - T Gogele (Germany) 67, 76, 68, 71.
283 - G Ryall (England) 74, 69, 71, 69; S Pullan (England) 70, 70, 69, 74; A
