<HEADLINE>Havelange's stranglehold must be broken Time to give game back to the people</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175752</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOAO Havelange travels the globe like some benign overlord with the interests
of the world's poor occupying a large place in his heart. Sometimes he is
photographed with groups of Third World children, smiling down on them as
though he will make everything better and ensure decent futures for all of them.
Some might suggest, however, that instead of offering warm comfort his taut
grin might reveal that coldness which seemed evident when Margaret Thatcher
tried to speak softly and in motherly fashion to the nation. The former Prime
Minister usually appeared darkly threatening those times when she was
attempting to empathise with her people.
Whatever else Havelange may be, the Brazilian president of FIFA could be a
student of Machiavelli. How else could he be in his sixth four-year term as
leader of all of the world's footballing nations and threatening to hang around
for a seventh after the 1998 World Cup finals in France. He must be resisted.
When the finals open in France, Havelange will be 82 and, although age often is
little more than a state of mind, that really will be too old. Already he has
been around too long and claims of his greatness, as spouted by those who have
propped him up all these years, should be dismissed as no more than propaganda.
Many may have self-interest at heart, nothing else.
Like all leaders Havelange is a master of playing people off against one
another while surrounding himself with acolytes. Travel is undertaken in style
and comfort and domestic association would be wise to accommodate all the
president's men. Havelange, with the might of FIFA behind him, is a powerful
man.
Dissenters don't disappear in the still of a dark night but, suddenly, doors
which used to swing open might become jammed. Favours may be scattered
elsewhere and the pavement outside the establishment can be an exteremely cold
place.
FIFA, like the SFA and all other member associations, is a pyramid structure of
committees which makes manipulation possible. Say and do the right things, as
perhaps suggested by the main office, and a person's future could be assured
with that delegate absorbed into the system to be relied on to cast the correct
vote at the correct time.
Havelange has fended off challenges to his authority from within UEFA in the
past, but it is said the Europeans remain resentful of the president's almost
total dominance of the sport. UEFA were also further annoyed when some of their
people were removed from key FIFA committees after Lennart Johansson, UEFA's
president, challenged unsuccessfully Havelange's re-election last year.
However, Johansson is strong also and the struggle for supremacy between the
two continues with Europe's man having won a victory last week when both
presidents and the heads of the six FIFA regional confederations met in Zurich.
That gathering decided there should be a reorganisation of the sport by
widening the spread of authority and by boosting profits from the World Cup.
These changes were at Johansson's insistence and he also secured an agreement
in principle to rotate the World Cup finals on a strictly geographical basis,
although the decision on which continent would get the first open slot was
deferred. Japan or South Korea will host the 2002 finals, Europe, with Germany
already favourites, want the 2006 event.
South Africa also has made it clear they would want the finals at some point
and, of course, South America are complaining loudly that they haven't been
hosts since 1986.
During his lengthy reign Havelange, who ousted Sir Stanley Rous in 1974 and is
the only non-European to hold the FIFA presidency, has manoeuvred himself into
a position of power which is almost invincible. He angered many within football
and outraged the outside world when he promised Nigeria the next World Youth
Championship in 1997.
This so-called guardian of the people's game toured the African country on the
eve of the execution of nine human rights activists, and his presence there was
at odds with international condemnation of Nigeria's military regime. It was
the behaviour of a man perhaps distanced from reality, yet Havelange is the man
his people within FIFA would have the rest of us believe is a caring,
grandfatherly figure who feels for the under-privileged and all peoples
supressed by poverty and force.
Havelange comes from a country which carries the Third World's largest foreign
debt and the upper-class whites do not do enough to alleviate the suffering or
offer hope to the masses who exist in heart-breaking poverty.
Football needs a new leader, someone with more compassion and feeling and also
a president with vision. Johansson, who is 66 and will be too old himself soon,
was said to be one of those outraged by Havelange's visit to Nigeria and the
Swede should press ahead with his challenge to the Brazilian and continue to
dispute his actions.
Johansson is striving to erode Havelange's power base and has presented a
reform document, Vision, which is currently being discussed in the corridors of
power and the early indications are that UEFA's president is gaining ground,
although Johansson would never make the mistake of underestimating an opponent
with the durability of Havelange.
However, last week's Zurich meeting agreed to UEFA's proposals to boost
television and marketing income from the World Cup by opening up the bidding to
competition. FIFA's contract with its long-time marketing arm, ISL, expires in
1998 and offers have already been received for the selling of the 2002 World
Cup in Asia, worth an estimated $1 billion.
UEFA haved long believed the rights to the World Cup should generate at least
$800m, even though the 1994 World Cup finals in America brought in only $184m.
UEFA feel they have been sold short and they and the other regional
confederations want a greater share of the profits in future. UEFA and
Johansson also want the time-span of future presidential reigns clearly
defined, but Havelange and his people have not moved on that yet.
Naturally, they wish to perpetuate their rule and it is likely, if and when
Havelange decides he has to go - although that might only happen when the
pall-bearers finally catch up with him - he might have in mind a replacement of
his own who could challenge Johansson or any other European. Havelange has not
built a power-base around himself and his chosen ones only to have it crumble
when he relaxes his grip.
The power struggle between him and Johansson, the only European to criticise
Havelange repeatedly and to stand up to him in public, will continue and grow
in intensity. It is one we should hope Johansson wins, because the game can do
without more of Havelange's posturing and power-broking. He has enjoyed enough
of the good things the game has to offer and it is time someone more in touch
with the people took over.
Johansson is a determined and strong-willed character who understands the
machinations of those who crave position and influence and he is well aware of
the dangers in having one man in possession of so much power. He feels the
workings of FIFA should be more transparent to outsiders and wants to introduce
a greater degree of democracy into the world association and who could possibly
wish to deny either of these desires? Only one man perhaps, which is why
Johansson must fight on.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
