<HEADLINE>Higgins through despite errors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175753</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN Higgins claimed his third victory of the season over Jimmy White in last
night's Royal Liver Assurance UK Championship third-round clash - and then
branded it ``one of the worst matches I have ever played in.''
The match was expected to be one of the highlights of the Preston tournament
with the winner facing 1991 champion John Parrott or Welshman Mark Williams in
the quarter-finals. After clinching a 9-6 success, Higgins described it as
``rubbish'' while White admitted: ``That was total garbage.''
White added: ``We were missing balls that weren't even pressure shots.''
Higgins, who had beaten Mark King and Alain Robidoux with fluent displays to
set up his showdown with White, said: ``I suppose you cannot make 100 breaks in
every frame unless you happen to be Stephen Hendry.''
The 20-year-old was never behind in the match after taking the first frame with
a 55 clearance. White levelled at 1-1 with a 66 break - his highest of the
match - but then trailed 4-1 and 5-3 at the end of the first session.
When the match resumed last night White should have snatched the ninth frame
but missed a yellow and Higgins went three frames ahead once more. Higgins had
a run of 73 to seal the match in the fifteenth frame.
Earlier, world No.12 Nigel Bond took the first three frames of the second
session to overwhelm Welshman Wayne Jones 9-2 and now plays Peter Ebdon, who
finished off Steve Lee 9-5.
History was made on Saturday when Hendry became the first player to achieve the
perfect clearance of 147 three times in competition.
Hendry, who made a maximum also in the world cham-pionship in Sheffield earlier
this year, repeated the feat in the fifth frame of his 9-2 success over Gary
Wilkinson.
The Scot then revealed the moment he knew he was on cue to compile this latest
147. ``I had made 72 when I began to realise the possibility,'' explained
Hendry. ``I could have taken a lower-value colour at that point, but you don't
get many chances to make a maximum, so I decided to go for it.
``It wasn't as nerve-racking this time because the one at The Crucible was my
first on television. However, the heart beat a little faster toward the end.''
In addition, Hendry also knocked in breaks of 100 and 105 to extend his total
of centuries in the event to seven - making it 18 for the season and 316 in his
career. In the quarter-final he will meet an Irishman - either Dennis Taylor or
Ken Doherty.
Weekend results (third round): S Hendry (Scotland) beat G Wilkinson (England)
9-2; P Ebdon (England) beat S Lee (England) 9-5; N Bond (England) beat W Jones
(Wales) 9-2; J Higgins (Scotland) beat J White (England) 9-6.
Today's order of play: 2pm and 7pm: K Doherty (Ireland) v D Taylor (N Ireland);
2pm: R O'Sullivan (England) v C Small (Scotland); 7pm: A Hicks (England) v J
Wattana (Thailand). Both matches resume 7pm tomorrow.
