<HEADLINE>McClair again must wait and wonder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175755</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN McClair could return to the substitutes' bench for Manchester United
tonight despite having scored two goals recently against Coventry.
United manager Alex Ferguson must decide between Paul Scholes and McClair
before naming his team to face Nottingham Forest at the City Ground. Scholes,
United's top scorer this season with 10 goals, missed the 4-0 victory at
Highfield Road because of a cold - but may get the nod.
``There is always that possibility,'' said McClair. ``But I always look at
whatever game I play in, in the same way. I try and enjoy it and take whatever
I can from the game. We must wait and see what happens, but the club and team
are more important than individuals.''
United are out to narrow the gap on Premiership leaders Newcastle to three
points, and Ferguson said: ``Brian has given this club great service. He has
never complained and has always set out his stall to make sure whatever I ask
him to do he has the mental capacity and strength to do it.''
Forest's last match in the Premiership resulted in a 7-0 defeat at Blackburn,
which ended an unbeaten league record stretching over 25 matches. However, they
put the trouncing behind them in their next game by beating Lyon in a UEFA Cup
game.
Paul McGregor, who scored against the French side, is injured and will have a
fitness test before the United match. Forest also will be without Dutchman
Bryan Roy, out for a month after a cartilage operation, and striker Jason Lee,
who has yet to overcome a thigh injury.
</TEXT>
