<FLAG>euroview </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175757</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT do Malcolm Rifkind, George Galloway and Kenneth Clarke, to name but a few,
have in common? You won't guess so I'll tell you. They've all been pictured in
the papers recently puffing fat cigars.
Time was I would have envied them. What bliss, the curl of aromatic, blue
wisping smoke, the satisfying, blood-tingling fix from a fragrant corona. How
beautifully it complimented a glass of after-dinner malt.
My trouble was I could never smoke them in moderation. When you've been a
cigarette addict, especially a 40-a-day man like me, you cannot smoke cigars
without inhaling.
I know. There was a time an age ago when I quit cigarettes and cigars for two
whole years. One day, on the first tee at Gleneagles, I found myself being
tempted by a free packet of five half-coronas by the Wills tobacco people who
were sponsoring a press golf outing. Just one, I thought . . .
My colleague Ian Paul from the sports desk tutt-tutted when he saw I was losing
the battle of will.
``Look, if you must give in here's how to smoke without getting hooked again,''
he said. ``Just take a very deep breath before you take a draw - that way, you
physically can't inhale.''
Rubbish, of course. By the time I was on the 18th I had binged on the lot. But
I never went back to cigarettes. Worse, I became one of those idiots who think
they're doing themselves a favour by ignoring cigarettes in favour of deadlier
small cigars. Soon I was doing 10 and sometimes 20 cigarillos a day.
Next month I will have gone nine years without a smoke of any kind. I can
honestly say it is something I never - well, almost never - even think about.
Except at times like last week when I saw that picture of Gorgeous George
pulling on an expensive cigar with all the evident pleasure of capricious
self-indulgence.
The good news for those of us who have kicked the habit is that Europe is on
our side. Life for those who still choose to smoke, at least in non-consenting
company, is going to become yet more difficult.
Anyone who has visited the United States recently knows the problem. Smoking in
America is now near to treason. Its suppression is imposed with neo-Fascist
zeal. Smokers are hounded from restaurants, airports, hotels, even bars. They
cannot fly, travel by bus or rail, or even sit at their desks at work.
As a quitter, I sympathise with them, but only up to a point. I've gone
weedless long enough now to be offended by tobacco breath or by a stranger
recycling inhaled cigarette or pipe smoke in my face. But, like the kid
sniffing Bisto, I still love the bouquet of a passing cigar.
Philip Morris, the US tobacco conglomerate, is currently in a fight to the
death with the anti-smoking lobby in America and engulfed in litigation as it
runs a multi-million dollar publicity campaign claiming smokers are persecuted
and deprived of their individual rights.
Well, they have just made themselves a powerful enemy in the European
Commission which is taking up cudgels on behalf of non-smokers. In justifying
its partisanship, the commission argues that six major studies have all
concluded passive smoking definitely causes lung cancer, especially in children.
Smokers should be more considerate about the rights of non-smokers, it says,
pointing out smokers enjoy the same civil liberties in law as non-smokers. This
is not an area in which Brussels legislates, at least not just yet, perhaps for
the simple reason that smoking on the Continent is still much more prevalent
than it is in Britain.
Europe's turn of the screw on its smokers will be cranked another notch next
week when health ministers meet to discuss a proposed ban on tobacco
advertising. This is a touchy subject because the commission, to its shame,
gives far more of its millions every year to tobacco growers than it does to
the relief of cancer. For once commissioners will not be able to claim the
moral high ground.
British Tories, who don't want newspapers banned from carrying advertising,
will find the debate tricky, not least because the tobacco giants are
traditional funders of the Conservative Party.
If you are a smoker you might find all of this depressing. Be warned, it gets
worse.
You know how social trends in the United States inevitably become all the rage
in Britain? The really bad news is the Americans are now campaigning for an end
to drinking.
</TEXT>
