<HEADLINE>Road to Nirvana, Traverse Theatre, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175758</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEY everybody, guess what? Playwright Arthur Kopit has had this penetrating
insight into the workings of Hollywood. He reckons it's run by money-grabbing
philistines with shallow personalities and drug habits. And he's not afraid to
say so! Devastating critique, or what?
I wouldn't want to suggest the heart of the international movie industry is not
worthy of satire - Tim Robbins's The Player proves otherwise, for one - but
Road to Nirvana barely manages to tell us what we already know, never mind
broadening our knowledge, subverting it and throwing it back in debased form.
Take the portrayal of the titular pop star Nirvana (Tara Hugo), a send-up of
Madonna (the grunge associations presumably passing the playwright by). The
problem is we are all so thoroughly well-versed not only in the outward
achievements, the hit singles, the ambitious personality, the giant ego, but
also in the nature of the hype itself - our showbiz appetite being so voracious
we eat the machinery once we've chewed through the product - there really is
very little left to say.
So superstars surround themselves with yes-men to confirm an overblown sense of
their own importance - so what?
Kopit could have got away with it if he hadn't written something so
theatrically static. In Justin Greene's production it's a real
tables-and-chairs show, in the way of the most routine modern American drama,
with Michael Taylor's sets leaving nothing to the imagination.
It can be quite funny and there are some sparky stand-offs between Stephen
Frost, as a bullying would-be producer, and Lou Hirsch, excellent as his
degraded partner. However, lacking in purpose or surprise, the play never
survives longer than the moment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
