<TEXT>
THERE was a big sign on a lorry parked just round the corner from Kingston
Heath golf course in Melbourne yesterday. It read: ``Take no prisoners, Great
White Shark. Go get 'em, Greg.'' It was signed by Mark, with a note in the
corner saying: ``Dad helped.''
``That sort of thing's really special. It makes you feel nice,'' smiled Greg
Norman, the Great White Shark in question, who had been and gone and got 'em
and won the Australian Open.
The 40-year-old Australian surged home in 32, four under par, for a round of 68
and a total of 278, 10 under, and two shots better than fellow Aussie Peter
McWhinney. Frenchman Jean-Louis Guepy and Craig Parry, another Australian, tied
for third on 281.
``No win is ever easy,'' said Norman, who proved it with his second shot at the
thirteenth, where his drive finished on a sandy lie under the trees to the
right of the fairway. ``I hit a No.7-iron and I had to slice it 40 yards in a
130-yard shot.''
The ball ended 18 feet from the hole, the putt went in for a birdie 3 and,
since it was sandwiched between two birdie 4s, it took Norman to the head of
affairs on nine under par, alongside the tenacious McWhinney.
He, Guepy, Parry, and Stuart Appleby, a young Australian of whom great things
are expected, all shared the lead at one time or another, but they all slipped
away over the closing holes.
Norman hit a No.2-iron second shot from 212 yards just as he wanted at the
459-yard, par-4 seventeenth and holed the 40-foot putt to seal victory.
The first prize of #76,500 was less than John Daly won in the casino, where he
had more success on the blackjack table than he did on the course. A round of
73 left him sharing forty-third place on 294, but it was the 80 on Saturday
that ended his chances, a 9 at the sixteenth, where he four-putted, doing most
of the damage. Leading aggregates (Australian unless stated):
