<HEADLINE>Rumpelstiltskin, Cumbernauld Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175760</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OFPANTS - the official pantomime watchdog - has been to Cumbernauld . . . and
declares that - after a few false sightings in other venues - panto-time has
really, truly, started.
Checklist at the ready, Ofpants was able to tick the following essentials:
audience participation, traditional tomfoolery - a bit of slapdash baking, a
ghostly flap, rampant flatulence, that sort of thing - and a very definite
set-to between good and evil, rooted in the Grimm scenario of Rumpelstiltskin,
but with equally grim echoes of our own market forces, for the sometimes
(overlooked) element of sharp topicality.
That said, the Cumbernauld show is more a piece of children's theatre than a
full-blown pantomime. Writer/director Simon Sharkey has fashioned a strong
narrative which incorporates the rarely-staged fairy tale within an appealing
wider framework.
The miller's daughter forced to spin straw into gold now has a friend - David
McGowan's Simon, a gentle wild boy who lives in the woods (which cunningly
allows for frequent appearances by cuddly furries, much pounced on by front-row
tots) and who upholds shinier values than the ``don't just get rich, get
richer'' greed factor that Rumpelstiltskin (a throatily threatening Tony
Ventre) relies on to beguile the king and country.
This is a show that needs the kids to listen, as well as shout out - not always
a priority with some age groups. But Sharkey's script, with Rumpelstiltskin's
world domination spell constantly linking the different adventures and setbacks
together, quite obviously caught the imagination of the young and the very
young children all around me on Saturday afternoon.
They weren't just enthralled, they were involved in puzzling it out. It also
looks marvellous - and a green forest glade which translates at the push of a
prop into market-place, throne room, or bedroom, which Richard Cherns's music
adds in wispy magical shivers of its own.
Well done the team for bringing a favourited but somewhat neglected classic
tale of good gold and greed before a new generation. And for doing it with such
style. I found myself thinking - this is the stuff that Disney used to be made
on, complete with winsome animals and, of course, a highly-animated cast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fine print worth the study</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>visual arts</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175761</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In the age of desk-top publishing,
Clare Henry finds handmade books all the more noteworthy
Approaching Christmas, art exhibitions have a lighter touch, as though the
festive season and dark nights demand cheerful, witty, optimistic work. And
diversity. The current rash of new shows also demonstrates the high calibre of
indigenous Scottish art.
We are fortunate to live in a place that produces talented folk like Frances
Walker, Glen Scoullar, and Laura Harrison who, with a whisk of a brush, can
transport us to Tiree's idyllic beaches or sunny Tuscany.
But first there's Brought to Book at Glasgow's Collins Gallery till December
21. In a former life I was, fleetingly, a typographer. I still have a fondness
for fine print, especially when combined with beautiful images. Here 70 artists
show 200 handmade books, from immaculate letterpress (like Norman Ackroyd's Co
Mayo or Llandogo's Old Stile Press who produced George Mackay Brown's Margins
or W S Graham's Letters enhanced Douglas Thomson's woodcuts) to wacky pop-up
books, books with spinning pages, books in the heel of a shoe, covered in
tartan dolls - even books that have to be cooked to be read!
As you see, artists books are something special, often produced in very small
editions - a mere three-of-a-kind - and intended for intimate perusal by a
single ``reader''. In an age when desk-top publishing and electronic imaging
make uniform printing child's play, it might seem perverse that artists beaver
away at something unique. But the appeal of creating a work of art to be
scrutinised in the hand, while still providing the element of surprise that
turning over a new leaf brings, has obviously not palled.
Curator Morag Davidson sets the show in context with an introduction of
Matisse's famous Jazz (an all-time great), Warhol's Index Book and Alan Davie's
Magic Reader. Other big names include Jarman, Kosuth, Gillik, Breakwell,
Beattie, Tyson, Simon Cutts, Les Coleman, Cornelia Parker - and Simon
Lewandowski whose books are embellished with electric motors.
Scots to look out for include Elspeth Lamb, with a brand-new Birch Wood, a
dream of lyrical lithographic washes combined with text; Eileen Lawrence's
gentle watercolours; Jacki Parry's handmade paper book; Hamilton Finlay's
Garden Proposal from his son Alec's Morning Star Publications; Robert
Hamilton's Facadism; Margaret Hunter's Binding, printed in Berlin; and Karen
Strang's Insanadiorama.
While artists like Nicholas McDowall can conjure pure typography to make a
Charade book of humerous Bodoni typeface characters (25), Karen Strang's 28-box
series pushes the concept to its limit. Yet it's an eyecatching exhibit and
beneath its superficial, banal, sweet, and happy surface - with silver sparkle
hearts and roses, plastic Barbie dolls, madonnas, and toy clothes pegs - lurks
a dark subtext. Burning books is still seen as a sin. Burning women has not
long gone out of fashion.
``Lift the lid off any house, and there are undercurrents. Fred and Rosemary
West are the extreme example,'' says Strang. ``I began looking at witchcraft
around Stirling, where I live, and extended my research into the male view that
women, `bad or mad', need to be punished, via Freud, hysteria, insanity, and
religion.''
The last legal execution of Scottish women was in 1727. The Koran states ``men
have authority over women because God made the one superior to the other'' and
recommends beating.
In the 1950s assertive American housewives were routinely subjected to
lobotomy. Even the 1993 Journal of Psychiatry lists Plica, a medical condition
where ``high nervous female tension was found to vent itself in tangled hair''.
Stang interprets true yet bizarre historical examples, from Snow White to
eggplants and the Marian Cult. My favourite is Housework Fairy, ``discovered
between a skirting board and a settee''.
n FRANCES WALKER's childhood walks along the Ayr coast inform spectacular
screenprints commissioned for the new South Ayr Hospital, which she hopes will
provide something ``calm and contemplative for apprehensive pre-op patients''.
(At #200 they are cheap too.)
At Edinburgh's Talbot Rice she records other journeys, both literal and
spiritual, in two huge, memorable eight-panel screens, Machair Walk and
Atlantic Watch. They are a triumph - and a paean to her beloved wide horizons,
leaden skies, and spatial panoramas of the green, blue unfenced world of Tiree.
Less lyrical, but evoking the stubborn rocks and strata of the land, her pencil
carves the track of the Dun Burn, the dunes, Craignish strand: in snow or storm
an intelligent celebration of the land.
n AT Glasgow's Billcliffe Gallery Glen Scouller explores Italy. The heat sears
off the pantiles; the deep purple of Trevi, Val d'Elsa, Assisi, and San
Gimignano looks welcome. Known for his big, fluid watercolours, these new oils
have an engaging spontaneity. However, pattern has gained the upper hand in the
gate and hen pictures; in others heavy-handed bravado replaces panache. These
traits are symptomatic of a transitional phase; interesting to see what comes
next.
n CLAIRE BANKS has also been to Italy, courtesy of Alastair Salvesen's generous
travel award. Minimal and flat, I was disappointed by these pale, misty grey
compositions of colonnades, windows, and doorways. The best is Santo Spirito
with its precise yellow slits. At the RSA till December 13.
n AT William Hardie, Laura Harrison and Francis Farmer show colourful pictures.
Farmer views characteristic architectural motifs from Findhorn, Wiltshire,
Aberdour, and Italy from on high to create overlap designs. Harrison
immortalises flowers from her Whitecraigs garden in lush still lifes of roses,
lilies, carnations, and sunflowers. The small studies, like Amaryllis,
Courtyard, and Yellow Jug are a delight.
n MEANWHILE don't miss Sam Bough's lively nineteenth-century landscapes of
Dysart, Fife in general, and Newhaven at Bourne Fine Art, Edinburgh; Wendy
McMurdo's spectacular photographic illusions at Portfolio Gallery, or the
intense poetic blue installation by Moon Beom and off-the-wall sequinned fish
by Bul Lee; both in Korean Artists at the Fruitmarket.
As I said, diversity is in the air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Euro route is still unclear</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>in touch sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175762</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER day and yet another fresh initiative. The weekend news that the English
and the Welsh have hammered out a plan which creates a new Anglo-Welsh league
from next season begs the question, where does that leave us in Scotland?
The Irish might well be asking questions along similar lines, but at least they
are already involved in Europe with their provincial sides. In Scotland, you
get the feeling that the game is charging on at an unfettered pace and we are
being left at the starting gate.
Basically, the Anglo-Welsh deal is this. Both domestic leagues will continue as
normal and the top four clubs will fly their respective national flags in
Europe. The remaining top eight clubs will play in the new cross-border league
and there will also be Twickenham and Cardiff games between the English and
Welsh cup and league champions.
The agreement was hammered out against a backdrop of ``club power'' in both
countries, the clubs flexing their muscles with the threat of a breakaway from
the national unions. The driving force is the need to pay the players, with the
potential revenue from glamorous club competitions being seen as the means to
that end.
So, the English and the Welsh have set in place a structure which, once fleshed
out with sponsors and a TV deal, has the makings of a nice little earner and -
equally importantly - a competition which the paying public will want to watch.
Meanwhile, north of the Cheviots what do we have to look forward to? Nobody
knows, and that is the sad truth of the matter. We will be in Europe next
season but whether we will be represented by club or district sides remains,
still, a matter for conjecture and it is high time that this matter was
resolved once and for all.
On Saturday past, the club championship would have been decided had it not been
for the messy postponements caused by the international commitments of the
country's leading players. Surely the clubs should have known by now whether
they were playing for a place in Europe or not.
Representation by district sides - or some hybrid amalgamation of the districts
- is the route favoured by the Scottish Rugby Union. Whether this remains the
case we do not know. We simply have not been told.
On the basis of playing strength, districts make sense. We have said that
before. But then what happens? The opening game in the district championship
between the the Exiles and the South, which was to have been played next
weekend, is cancelled. Cancelled mark you, not postponed, because premiership
business remains unfinished. Oh, what a tangled web we weave . . .
At a stroke, the district championship, from which so much is expected by
Murrayfield officialdom, is diminished and devalued. It is difficult, in the
face of such apparent perversity, to argue with clubs who say that they and not
the districts should be allowed to fly the saltire in Europe next season.
At Bridgehaugh on Saturday, Stirling County and Melrose - two of the most
prominent members of the pro-clubs lobby, and throw in Watsonians and
Boroughmuir, maybe, for good measure - were arguing privately that perhaps with
their present pool of players they might not be able to compete with the Baths
et al but if they got their hands on the pot of gold that European competition
guarantees then they could build teams to compete with the best.
And, they say, they could keep Scotland's star players in Scotland and, even
more pertinently, lure those who have gone south - or are about to - back to
their ain folk. They make a pretty convincing case.
Time marches on. We are almost at the turn of the year. What we principally
require is a decision from the SRU. The clubs have shown over the past couple
of months that they are, mostly, all at sea. The issue of European competition,
not least from a financial standpoint, is of the utmost importance. The time
for a decision is now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rovers pair to stay in the fold</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175763</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BLACKBURN'S Graeme Le Saux and David Batty have buried the hatchet and are
staying with the champions, manager Ray Harford said yesterday after this draw
in London.
Club chairman Robert Coar will issue a statement today outlining the punishment
the England pair will face for last week's altercation in Moscow.
It will be at least one week's wages, a sanction Le Saux accepts but that Batty
was said to be unhappy with, fuelling suggestions that the club are prepared to
sell both men, with Arsenal and Leeds among the potential purchasers.
``Both are staying,'' said Harford, praising their apparent Highbury
reconciliation. ``It looked that way on the pitch - they were playing close
together as usual and I think they'll feel better for having played that game.
``They have sorted it out between themselves, and we have sorted it out too -
the fines and everything. We've tried to handle it as clean as we can, to be
firm and fair,'' he said.
The manager expects Coar to signal that an incident which split the Rovers
dressing room is over as far as the club is concerned, though both players
still face UEFA sanctions.
``Officially we want to make it as clear as possible that the affair is
ended,'' said Harford. ``I have spoken to Gordon Taylor (PFA chief executive)
and he was of the opinion that we should make the statement, take whatever
action we propose and, if UEFA or the FA want to know, we will tell them what
we have done.''
Yesterday's result gave Rovers only their second away point of the season. ``It
was important after the week that we've had that we went out and performed like
that,'' said Harford. ``We needed an away result, an away point.''
And the result came a no great surprise to Arsenal manager Bruce Rioch. ``After
the events of the last couple of weeks, Blackburn could have gone one of two
ways,'' he said. ``It either de-motivates you or you turn it to your advantage.
They set their stall out and were difficult to overcome.''
Rioch was disappointed with his side, adding: ``That was a disjointed
performance. It was a battle for us right from the early part of the game and
those are games you can lose 1-0.
``So there is a degree of satisfaction that after conceding four goals in the
last couple of games, we kept a clean sheet.''
Neither manager would criticise referee Graham Poll, who booked seven players,
with Rioch gagged by the FA after having criticised Martin Bodenham after a
recent game against Chelsea.
``I don't want to talk about the referee - I've had a letter from the FA in
regard to the last comments I made,'' said the manager.
The best chance of the afternoon yesterday came after 15 minutes when Mike
Newell beat the Arsenal central defenders to a cross from Stuart Ripley, but a
well-timed tackle from Lee Dixon on the six-yard line saved the day for the
Gunners.
Rovers had the ball in the net inside the last minute when Newell turned in a
cross from Alan Shearer, only for the goal to be wiped out by an offside flag,
much to the delight of the Arsenal support.
Arsenal 0, Blackburn Rovers 0
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Royal SNO, Glasgow Royal Concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175764</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN a concert consists of works by Tchaikovsky, Rachmaninov, and Shostakovich,
it is safe to guess that at least two of them will be stock favourites. But
there was nothing predictable about Alexander Lazarev's choice of music on
Saturday.
Even the structure of the evening was unusual, with a leisurely orchestral
suite in the first half, a tight-knit concerto and symphony in the second.
Surprisingly, given the conservatism of RSNO audiences, there was a full house,
which suggested a degree of trust in Lazarev as a purveyor of neglected
Tchaikovsky and in the brilliant young Jean-Yves Thibaudet as soloist in a by
no means user-friendly piece of Rachmaninov.
It was, in fact, Tchaikovsky's second suite that was the evening's revelation,
if not in performance terms, it's most complete success. Music as idiosyncratic
as this - the third of its five movements calls for a band of accordionists -
needed to be played with more character and charm than Lazarev's efficiently
cool but rather ruthless conducting of it allowed.
The accordion episodes, played in rather strait-laced fashion by two members of
the orchestra, went for nothing, and the slow movement lacked atmosphere. Nor
could a programme note that failed to mention the accordions or to provide a
meaning for the word ``kazachok'' (a species of folk dance) have been said to
serve the work's best interests.
But the Rachmaninov, which can sometimes sound like pages of empty passage-work
in search of a theme, suffered no such setbacks in a performance so vividly
integrated that neither its structure nor content was ever in doubt. Even
better was Shostakovich's ninth symphony, a masterpiece beneath whose terse,
brittle jollity lies an abyss of melancholy and bitterness.
Lazarev's lacerating performance conveyed its tensions with chilling,
disturbing precision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Simpson strikes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975175765</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE five-strong Scottish contingent in the Great Britain women's hockey squad
certainly can't be accused of not pulling their weight in the successful
Olympic qualifying campaign in Cape Town, for they were responsible for nine of
the team's 10 goals.
Topping the British scorers' list was Rhona Simpson. She had failed to find the
target for Britain in 43 internationals, but she hit form in Cape Town, scoring
four in their last five matches, including the confrontation on Saturday
against South Africa.
Simpson hit the target after 29 minutes meeting a cross from the right by Jane
Sixsmith with all the energy she could muster, to give Great Britain a 1-0
victory which should have been more impressive.
Indeed, it might have been had Susan MacDonald enjoyed some luck, for she hit
the crossbar with a penalty.
The other contributors to the Scottish scoring tally were Susan Fraser (three),
and Pauline Robertson (two). Britain's victory gave them second place in the
event and they go to Atlanta with victors Korea, along with Germany, Argentina,
and Holland where they meet defending champions Spain, world champions
Australia, and hosts USA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sparks fly in Arsenal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175766</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Just when everything looked lost
in France, the BBC SSO came
up with a real winner,
says MICHAEL TUMELTY
THE experience was likened to touring Poland in the mid-eighties: ``We don't
know where we're going, how we're going to get there, if we're going to get
there, or how long it's going to take,'' said a veteran BBC Scottish Symphony
Orchestra musician, as the 72-strong orchestra piled on to three coaches for a
motorway race between Paris and Metz in an attempt to beat a national transport
strike on Friday and get the SSO to its next concert.
The orchestra was never supposed to have been in Paris. The strike had meant
that the charter flight on its mini tour from Bordeaux in the south to Metz in
the north couldn't go, and only the persistent inquiry of the group's courier,
representing the promoters - the Paris-based IMG group - had uncovered a single
flight from Bordeaux to Orly airport in Paris; and one, moreover, that could
accommodate such a large party.
The concert in Metz was within a hair's breadth of being cancelled, and the
orchestra kept in Bordeaux. Having made it, the unanimous feeling in the party
was that it was worth it - in fact, that all the vicissitudes and uncertainties
gave the playing a real edge. Not only was the Arsenal concert hall in Metz an
absolute stunner - a cathedral in wood with an explosive acoustic - but the BBC
SSO, with conductor laureate Jerzy Maksymiuk, turned out a series of scorching
performances that brought it an ovation from the large crowd.
What, above all, made it worth it was a classic BBC SSO performance of James
MacMillan's percussion concerto, Veni, Veni Emmanuel, with soloist Evelyn
Glennie in consummately theatrical form, turning out a real display piece for
the audience.
Glennie has done this concerto so many times now that she has its technical and
almost balletic elements absolutely at her fingertips. What was particularly
interesting was the SSO performance. It had had a single rehearsal session with
the concerto (which it had not played before) in Glasgow. Then there was the
first performance in Bordeaux which demonstrated the phenomenally rapid rate of
absorption of new material by this orchestra, which is used to turning over
unfamiliar music faster than any other.
But the Bordeaux performance lacked that final touch, where the whole thing is
absolutely together - there's an indefinable moment when you know that an
orchestra has stepped over a threshold with a piece and has acquired the feel
for its size, structure, shape, momentum, climaxes, and the rest. That happened
the next night in Metz, where, enhanced by an acoustic that gave the piece an
enormous impact, everything starting locking into place. It was a cracker.
As was the performance - typically Maksymiuk: big shapes, rolling climaxes,
boiling intensity - of Sibelius's Second Symphony, infinitely better played
than Dvorak's New World Symphony the previous night. And the same went for
Elgar's Introduction and Allegro, dry and boxy in the poor Bordeaux hall, big
and burnished in Metz.
The SSO doesn't get abroad much any more. (Who does?) The Metz Arsenal
performance, in a tiny if eventful little tour, made it absolutely worth the
bother.
Michael Tumelty reports on the future of the BBC SSO in Wednesday's music
column.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A place to make dreams come true</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joanna MacDonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975175767</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a well-known fact that dreams rarely come true. But if yours was to run
down the tunnel at Hampden with Kenny Dalglish, then the good news is that
after 1998, it will probably be possible.
For when the National Museum of Football opens in the new South Stand at
Hampden, there will be a themed, Disneyesque element to it and with advances in
technology you, too, could play with the greats.
Of course, the proposed museum will be, first and foremost, an archive for
football history with memorabilia coming from many different sources including
the League, SFA, and Queen's Park Football Club.
Austin Reilly, director of the national stadium, says Hampden is the ideal site
for the museum. ``After all, Queen's Park is the oldest club in the world still
playing at senior level. They treasure that tradition.''
The museum also will have an educational element. ``Many schools have projects
about football and the museum plan provides for educational rooms, so that
youngsters can come in and key in to the library and trace all they want to
know about the players and clubs,'' said Reilly.
``We are taking the museum plan very seriously. It's a crucial part of our
submission to the Millenium Commission.''
The museum would be the first of its kind in the UK. But what about another
first - a Museum of Sport for Scotland.
The country has a myriad of art and cultural galleries but nowhere that honours
the many sporting achievements of Scots in one place. As well as the Hampden
plan there is a golf museum in St Andrews but we could follow the example of
the Sports Museum of New England in Boston.
It incorporates computers, videos, interactive exhibits, and memorabilia from a
range of sports including baseball, golf, American football, boxing, racing,
basketball, and motorsport.
Visitors can trace the life of local man Johnny Kelly, a working-class hero who
became a sporting legend at marathon running. He ran in 61 Boston marathons and
was 83 when he gave up. During his career he was the winner twice and second
seven times and at 62, was as fast as he had been at 25.
There's even the opportunity for visitors to experience Heartbreak Hill as a
wheelchair competitor.
Many cases are given over to exhibits of strips and details of classic baseball
clashes and there is a fascinating insight into ferocious contests between Yale
and Harvard.
Football is also covered in the museum. There is a line-up photograph of the
Clan MacPherson team of 1928. With names like Anderson, Munro, MacTavish,
Haldane, and Dundas, it's plain that Boston immigrants from Great Britain
didn't just come from Ireland.
There's even a programme from a game in 1928 when Rangers went to Boston. The
league-and-cup winners played in front of a crowd of 10,000. And in 1967 the
Shamrock Rovers of Boston played Dundee in May and then Dundee United in June.
One aspect of the Boston example Scotland would hopefully avoid. The museum is
in a shopping mall. But others examples are worthwhile.
We would have the opportunity to pay tribute to the achievements of athletics
heroes like Allan Wells and Liz McColgan, boxing greats like Benny Lynch and
Ken Buchanan, motor racing legends Jim Clark and Jackie Stewart, and a myriad
of others. A Museum of Scottish Sport has much to commend it.
But if the planners are looking for ideas for the football museum there are
plenty of galleries and rooms that could be included at Hampden. Why not
include an interactive mock-up street so that today's youngsters can savour the
atmosphere of where the great players came from?
Or a virtual reality of all our yesterdays at Hampden. Essential equipment
would be two cans of lager. First you drink them and then teeter perilously on
them for a glimpse of the game through the swaying, 100,000 crowd.
There would have to be a punishment block. In it, Scotland's World Cup songs
could be constantly played. Imagine an hour of Yaba Daba Doo We Support the
Boys in Blue, followed by We're on the March with Ally's Army - if you dare.
The House of Horrors could show all the cruel and wicked deflections and
another gallery would have sunglasses provided on entry. This room would be
full of Arthur's jackets. Mind you, Mary Hateley could probably provide a few,
too.
Finally, there would be a look into the future. In 2020, Traynor would still be
bemoaning the state of football in this country and demanding that we follow
the example of the Ajax system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stand and deliver, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175768</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALAN Lorimer wrote that it was a blow to John Manson, the Stirling County prop
forward, perhaps to miss the chance to play against Western Samoa because he
had been selected as a replacement for the international last Saturday. So I
was sorry for John Manson. Better to play than watch any day.
He did, however, get a better chance to meet the Samoans than any member of the
Glasgow team. While Edinburgh, the South, the North and Midlands, and Scotland
all had fixtures against the tourists, there was no fixture for Glasgow.
Moreover, there were two fixtures in Edinburgh and none in Glasgow. Yet Glasgow
is the largest centre of population in Scotland.
What is the Scottish Rugby Union's game? Is it scared that rugby will develop
in Glasgow and become such a popular sport here that the Edinburgh and Border
domination of SRU officialdom will be overthrown?
And what about the Glasgow committee men? Are they not strong enough to obtain
for Glasgow its fair share of matches against touring sides? My recollection is
that the last two were well run at Old Anniesland and very well supported by
the Glasgow public.
A bit of democracy would do the trick.
David H Williams,
20 Kersland Drive,
Milngavie,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951127-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951127-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951127</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No feast but fine fare</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175769</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Currie 7, Jed-Forest 31
THERE had been talk that this end-of-league encounter, during which only pride
was at stake, would be given over to a feast of running rugby.
It did not quite turn out that way but on a perfect afternoon at Malleny Park,
we did see some flashes of what these teams do best - attacking at pace and
turning unlikely opportunities into exciting passages of play.
Jed-Forest's only disappointment from an excellent Premiership campaign is that
they are not going up to Division 1 as champions. Yet they can take
considerable satisfaction from the fact that they twice inflicted heavy defeats
on Currie in whose clubrooms the trophy will rest.
Jed coach Donald Miller was full of beans after his charges had run in four
tries and outplayed the champions in most departments.
He and his colleagues will be considering life after Gary Armstrong, who is now
99% certain to be teaming up with Rob Andrew at Newcastle.
It was probably Gary's best performance of the season, and with Ronnie
Kirkpatrick, Scott Foster, and Howler Brown in sparkling form, this was
approaching a vintage Jed display.
Currie were without playmaker Ally Donaldson, resting a sore back, and their
regular front row and seemed a little out of sorts.
So out of sorts, indeed, that they were 21 points adrift inside half an hour
after Brown, Kevin Barrie, and Norman Kerr - replacing hamstring tear victim
Chris Richards and playing a blinder - had crossed for tries and Kevin Amos
added goal points.
Amos, kicking superbly, added a penalty goal before big Mike Blair finished off
a Currie attack with a try which John Morrison converted.
It was left to Brown to finish matters off with a try as Jed took charge of the
game following hooker Alan Glen's concussion and departure to hospital for a
precautionary check-up. Amos, needless to say, added the final conversion.
Currie - D R Sheppard; G W Keen, M J Plumb, D C Wilson, S Forrester; J
Morrison, D Rogerson; D Massey, A R Glen, M Smith, C Eagle, M Blair, B W Ward,
F Thompson, S Logan. Replacements - N Matthews for Sheppard (59min), I Russell
for Glen (73).
Jed-Forest - K A Amos; B Hughes, A J Douglas, D R Hemming, M A K Yule; C J
Richards, G Armstrong; N A McIlroy, K W Barrie, G Kerr, B B Law, C R Hynd, S
Foster, R M Kirkpatrick, C J Brown. Replacement - N Kerr for Richards (6).
Referee - J L Bacigalupo (Edinburgh Wanderers).
SCORERS: Currie - Blair, 1t; Morrison, 1c. Jed-Forest - Amos, 4c, 1p; Brown,
2t; Barrie, 1t; Kerr, 1t.
</TEXT>
