<HEADLINE>The Rachmaninov Trio, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975175770</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN selecting the Rachmaninov Trio for their final act, the organisers of the
Fifth Anniversary Celebrations of Jewish Arts in Glasgow could hardly have made
a better choice. Incredible though it seems, this particular combination of
players has been appearing since only Mayfest last year, notwithstanding the
much longer association between violinist Lev Atlas and cellist Alexander
Volpov. In such a short space of time this trio has firmly established its
reputation for displaying a consummate musicianship that brings a thrilling
animation to whatever they play.
For this programme a familiar work by Mozart and Tchaikovsky respectively was
placed outside a piece by the now forgotten Moscheles, whose personal contacts
stretch from Salieri through Beethoven to Chopin.
The Mozart Trio K548 saw Phillip Silver particularly relaxed at the piano
despite an obvious throat irritation. His bright touch was echoed by his string
partners in a thoroughly jolly account.
Moscheles Piano Trio given here as a Scottish premiere 165 years after its
composition, was entertaining stuff with a couple of false endings and a cute
19th-century Disney view of Scotland in the Scherzo alla Scozzese movement. The
vintage performance though was reserved for Tchaikovsky's mammoth Piano Trio.
Only two movements, but the first can seem to go on a bit in less skilful
hands. These performers, however, have a magneticism that draws the listener in
to live the music with them. No surprise then that the Rachmaninov Trio now
have a recording contract.
