<HEADLINE>The mould must be broken to redefine our past</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>book of the week</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175771</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNITING THE KINGDOM, THE MAKING OF BRITISH HISTORY
Edited by Alexander Grant
and Keith Stringer
Routledge, #25
THE British history mentioned in the sub-title of this book carries a novel
connotation. In the traditions of the historical profession in the United
Kingdom, the terms British history and English history have been fairly well
interchangeable.
This, of course, echoed the linguistic usage of English people, who make little
distinction between Britain and England. They assume everything which happens
to England also happens to Britain as a whole, and nothing can happen to
Britain unless it happens to England.
Sloppy as the usage is, the run of historians has followed it. Until recently,
it was in no way abnormal for books of supposedly British history to give not
so much as an entry in the index for Scotland, Wales, or even Ireland. To
devote a chapter to them would have been thought superfluous to the point of
eccentricity.
Scottish, Welsh or Irish history were specialised subjects, like the history of
sewerage or the history of ladies' underwear. Almost by definition, they could
not enter into the great epic of British history, of which the vast bulk was
provided by English history, for the reasons just stated.
With this present collection of essays, however, the term British history comes
nearer to its literal meaning. In the principle, English, Scottish, Welsh and
Irish history are treated as deserving of equal consideration. On the axiom
that the whole is greater than the parts, a genuine effort is made to bring out
the contributions to the United Kingdom of its smaller nations.
The aims are thus worthy, though they do little more than respond to what
historians of the smaller nations have tried for years to put across to English
colleagues, to be greeted with indifference or scorn. What makes the difference
now is that English historians have been driven to conclude their grand
tradition no longer explains their country's past or present.
This sea-change is here ascribed primarily to John Pocock, a New Zealander who
has spent much of his career in the United States. In the volume's envoi,
addressed to the British, he recalls how he felt in 1973, ``after the great
divorce which occurred when you told us that you were Europeans, which we, as
New Zealanders, were not; so that after all those generations in which you had
allowed the notion of empire to shape your identity, we were to learn that you
cared as little for our past as for our future. What you did, of course, was
irrevocably and unilaterally to disrupt a concept of Britishness which we had
supposed we shared with you.''
That same year Pocock
Now he can say: ``I told you so.'' It is generally admitted Whig history's day
is done, and academics are busily constructing the new subject Pocock called
for. He himself is the guru of endeavour. In 1994, the prestigious annual
Anglo-American Conference of Historians sought to find out how far things have
gone. This book is the result.
Things seem to me to have some way to go yet. The collection has no doubt
turned out the better for being edited by two Scots at Lancaster University,
which for some reason is, in literature and politics as well as in history, a
more impressive centre of Scottish studies than most institutions in Scotland.
They reproduce 19 papers from the conference, covering 1000 years of history,
Most of them - despite the worthy intentions not quite all - deal in dense
academic detail with some aspect of relations among the four nations.
It still struck me as odd that not one comes from a Scot working in Scotland,
though there are three from Scots working in England. Nor is there any from a
Welshman. There are two from Irishmen, one each from North and South. The other
14 are from Englishmen, most out of the Golden Triangle of Oxford, Cambridge
and London.
Evidently Celts are unfit for high table just yet. There may be fears they
would get drunk and throw bread-rolls; some would. This is, however, not just a
matter for whinging Jocks. I was impressed with the aspersions on the whole
proceedings as in passing, before he discoursed learnedly on centralisation in
the sixteenth century, by Nicholas Canny, a wild-haired man from Galway who
still manages to be an excellent historian.
He had several criticisms of British history as conceived by recent coverts to
it. It is so fixated on high politics that it widens the existing gap between
political history and social or economic history. Then it implies an integrity
for the British Isles in excess of any that ever existed, and passes over links
between their different peoples and Europe. New British history often comes out
looking like old English history, for the concern is still with events regarded
as pivotal for England. Again, it ignores deep diversities which have made it
hard for the British peoples to live within one state. Finally, it can be
written by scholars who have not just English but three Celtic languages and
Latin.
Canny hits his nails right on the head. Talking to English historians, I have
often been struck by an immutable attitude among them. They might once have
dismissed Scottish history as an antiquarian subject on which there was nothing
useful to say for the period after 1707. If not, why had no Scottish historian
said it? Indeed, no Scottish historian had said very much.
Recently, the tune has changed somewhat. It will be conceded that more and
better history is now being written in Scotland than at any time since the
eighteenth century. But as this sets out from the view that Scotland was and is
a distinct community, a nation no less, it is regarded as lacking the wider
reference new British history demands.
In other words, there can be no internal dynamic in Scottish history, no
independence in it, to use a loaded word, and nothing to be undestood on its
own terms. While that view persists, I believe no properly British history will
be written, because it will remain too anglocentric.
So Scottish and other exotic historians should be allowed a place at the high
table. It might be found that, despite their odd table manners, they have
something to say.
</TEXT>
