<HEADLINE>Keeper could be out of action for eight weeks Walker blow is a sore one for Thistle to take</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975175772</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARTICK Thistle, crippled by injuries for most of the season and fighting for
premier division survival on a shoestring budget, were hit by more trouble at
the weekend when keeper Nicky Walker suffered a broken cheekbone during the 2-0
defeat by Raith Rovers at Firhill.
Walker took the knock early in the match, but played on with the help of pain
killers. ``I don't know who else was involved in the incident, but I felt it
straight away,'' said Walker. ``I was in a fair bit of pain in the latter
stages of the match.''
The keeper, who has been having an outstanding season, went straight to
hospital for X-rays and treatment, and the outcome is that he has played his
last match this year.
Said manager, Murdo MacLeod: ``I was pleased that Nicky got through the match,
but it was obvious the injury was causing him a lot of pain. He will now have
an operation and the doctor has told us he could be out for eight weeks. It's a
terrible blow on top of all the other things that have been happening.''
Thistle had five players undergoing fitness tests before Saturday's match, and
although four of them played, they were obviously not fully fit. Such is the
shallow strength of MacLeod's squad that such risks have to be taken.
``We have been trying to bring new faces to the club, but it isn't easy,'' said
the manager. ``However, we must do something positive. What with all the
injuries and other players nearing suspensions, we don't have a lot to fall
back on.''
That is one of the reasons why MacLeod will delay moving for a replacement for
Walker. Instead, he will field 26-year-old reserve keeper Mark Cairns, signed
from Gala Fairydean, against Aberdeen at Firhill on Saturday.
Said MacLeod: ``Our priority must be outfield players. Already we are talking
with three clubs about possible deals and something could move early in the
week.
``As far as the goalkeeping situation is concerned I am happy to go along with
Mark Cairns at the moment and then we will have another look at the situation.
He has been playing well in the reserves and will now get his chance to see
what he can do at the higher level.''
q.MORTON manager Allan McGraw did not forget about a farewell evening for new
Ranger Derek McInnes on Saturday, despite the fact that he had been rushed to
hospital in Dunfermline after suffering what was, at the time, believed to be
chest pain.
McInnes, who recently left Cappielow to join Rangers in a #300,000 deal, laid
on a special evening out for his former team-mates and McGraw was also invited.
The manager, however, was detained in the Dunfermline hospital - but he still
managed to get a special message to McInnes.
Morton coach John McMaster said yesterday: ``We were all worried about Allan.
But it is so typical of the man that when Eddie Morrison and I went into see
him on Saturday evening, he gave us a message for Derek.
``He told us to get in touch, let Derek know what had happened, and that he was
fine, and that everyone should enjoy the night out.
``But we were really worried beforehand for he was sweating and complaining of
a pain in his chest. However, he reckons it is a stomach problem.''
Tests were carried out over the weekend, and the Morton manager was allowed
home from the cardiology unit. What did he do? Watched the Coca-Cola Cup final
on television.
It's really difficult to keep a good man down, is it not?
</TEXT>
